\define explist(tagName)
<div class="tc-table-of-contents">
<<toc-selective-expandable '$tagName$' 'sort[title]'>>
</div>
\end
\define footnote(name text icon-name:"info-button")
<$button popup="$:/_document/state/footnote-$name$" class="tc-btn-invisible">{{$:/core/images/$icon-name$}}</$button>
<$reveal type="popup" state="$:/_document/state/footnote-$name$">
<div class="tc-drop-down">

!!&nbsp;$name$
$text$
</div>
</$reveal>
\end
\define info-box(bgColor iconColor iconType caption message)
<p style="background-color:$bgColor$;border-style:solid;padding:5px;">
<span style="fill:$iconColor$;">{{$:/core/images/$iconType$}}</span><span style="font-size:xx-large;vertical-align:top;"> $caption$</span><br>
<span style="vertical-align:top;">$message$</span>
</p>
\end

\define warning-message(message)
<<info-box
        bgColor: "#ff8"
        iconColor: "#f00"
        iconType: "warning"
        caption: "Warning"
        message: "$message$">>
\end

\define info-message(message)
<<info-box
        bgColor: "#f4f4f4"
        iconColor: "#66f"
        iconType: "info-button"
        caption: "Information"
        message: "$message$">>
\end

\define tip-message(message)
<<info-box
        bgColor: "#f4f4f4"
        iconColor: "#66f"
        iconType: "tip"
        caption: "Tip"
        message: "$message$">>
\end

\define nerdstuff(message)
<<info-box
        bgColor: "#f4f4f4"
        iconColor: "#66f"
        iconType: "options-button"
        caption: "NerdStuff"
        message: "$message$">>
\end

\define q-and-a(q a)
<<info-box
        bgColor: "#f4f4f4"
        iconColor: "#66f"
        iconType: "help"
        caption: "Q & A"
        message: "<b>Q: $q$</b><br/>A: $a$">>
\end
/*\
title: $:/_parser/PyShell
type: application/javascript
module-type: wikirule

The purpose of this block parser is to allow markup within a code block.

```
        %%%
        >>> ''print("Hello, World!")''
        Hello, World!
        %%%
```

\*/
(function(){

/*jslint node: true, browser: true */
/*global $tw: false */
"use strict";

exports.name = "pyshell";
exports.types = {block: true};

exports.init = function(parser) {
	this.parser = parser;
	// Regexp to match
	this.matchRegExp = /%%%\r?\n/mg;
};

exports.parse = function() {
	// Move past the match
	this.parser.pos = this.matchRegExp.lastIndex;

	// Parse the run including the terminator
	var tree = this.parser.parseInlineRun(/%%%/mg,{eatTerminator: true});

	// Return the classed span
	return [{
		type: "element",
		tag: "pre",
		children: tree
	}];
};

})();

        "$:/language/Help/fetch": {
            "title": "$:/language/Help/fetch",
            "description": "Fetch tiddlers from wiki by URL",
            "text": "Fetch one or more files over HTTP/HTTPS, and import the tiddlers matching a filter, optionally transforming the incoming titles.\n\n```\n--fetch file <url> <import-filter> <transform-filter>\n--fetch files <url-filter> <import-filter> <transform-filter>\n--fetch raw-file <url> <transform-filter>\n--fetch raw-files <url-filter> <transform-filter>\n```\n\nThe \"file\" and \"files\" variants fetch the specified files and attempt to import the tiddlers within them (the same processing as if the files were dragged into the browser window). The \"raw-file\" and \"raw-files\" variants fetch the specified files and then store the raw file data in tiddlers, without applying the import logic.\n\nWith the \"file\" and \"raw-file\" variants only a single file is fetched and the first parameter is the URL of the file to read.\n\nWith the \"files\" and \"raw-files\" variants, multiple files are fetched and the first parameter is a filter yielding a list of URLs of the files to read. For example, given a set of tiddlers tagged \"remote-server\" that have a field \"url\" the filter `[tag[remote-server]get[url]]` will retrieve all the available URLs.\n\nFor the \"file\" and \"files\" variants, the `<import-filter>` parameter specifies a filter determining which tiddlers are imported. It defaults to `[all[tiddlers]]` if not provided.\n\nFor all variants, the `<transform-filter>` parameter specifies an optional filter that transforms the titles of the imported tiddlers. For example, `[addprefix[$:/myimports/]]` would add the prefix `$:/myimports/` to each title.\n\nPreceding the `--fetch` command with `--verbose` will output progress information during the import.\n\nNote that TiddlyWiki will not fetch an older version of an already loaded plugin.\n\nThe following example retrieves all the non-system tiddlers from https://tiddlywiki.com and saves them to a JSON file:\n\n```\ntiddlywiki --verbose --fetch file \"https://tiddlywiki.com/\" \"[!is[system]]\" \"\" --rendertiddler \"$:/core/templates/exporters/JsonFile\" output.json text/plain \"\" exportFilter \"[!is[system]]\"\n```\n\nThe following example retrieves the \"favicon\" file from tiddlywiki.com and saves it in a file called \"output.ico\". Note that the intermediate tiddler \"Icon Tiddler\" is quoted in the \"--fetch\" command because it is being used as a transformation filter to replace the default title, while there are no quotes for the \"--savetiddler\" command because it is being used directly as a title.\n\n```\ntiddlywiki --verbose --fetch raw-file \"https://tiddlywiki.com/favicon.ico\" \"[[Icon Tiddler]]\" --savetiddler \"Icon Tiddler\" output.ico\n```\n\n"
        },

        "$:/language/Help/render": {
            "title": "$:/language/Help/render",
            "description": "Renders individual tiddlers to files",
            "text": "Render individual tiddlers identified by a filter and save the results to the specified files.\n\nOptionally, the title of a template tiddler can be specified. In this case, instead of directly rendering each tiddler, the template tiddler is rendered with the \"currentTiddler\" variable set to the title of the tiddler that is being rendered.\n\nA name and value for an additional variable may optionally also be specified.\n\n```\n--render <tiddler-filter> [<filename-filter>] [<render-type>] [<template>] [<name>] [<value>]\n```\n\n* ''tiddler-filter'': A filter identifying the tiddler(s) to be rendered\n* ''filename-filter'': Optional filter transforming tiddler titles into pathnames. If omitted, defaults to `[is[tiddler]addsuffix[.html]]`, which uses the unchanged tiddler title as the filename\n* ''template'': Optional template through which each tiddler is rendered\n* ''render-type'': Optional render type: `text/html` (the default) returns the full HTML text and `text/plain` just returns the text content (ie it ignores HTML tags and other unprintable material)\n* ''name'': Name of optional variable\n* ''value'': Value of optional variable\n\nBy default, the filename is resolved relative to the `output` subdirectory of the edition directory. The `--output` command can be used to direct output to a different directory.\n\nNotes:\n\n* The output directory is not cleared of any existing files\n* Any missing directories in the path to the filename are automatically created.\n* When referring to a tiddler with spaces in its title, take care to use both the quotes required by your shell and also TiddlyWiki's double square brackets : `--render \"[[Motovun Jack.jpg]]\"`\n* The filename filter is evaluated with the selected items being set to the title of the tiddler currently being rendered, allowing the title to be used as the basis for computing the filename. For example `[encodeuricomponent[]addprefix[static/]]` applies URI encoding to each title, and then adds the prefix `static/`\n* The `--render` command is a more flexible replacement for both the `--rendertiddler` and `--rendertiddlers` commands, which are deprecated\n\nExamples:\n\n* `--render \"[!is[system]]\" \"[encodeuricomponent[]addprefix[tiddlers/]addsuffix[.html]]\"` -- renders all non-system tiddlers as files in the subdirectory \"tiddlers\" with URL-encoded titles and the extension HTML\n\n"
        },
        "$:/language/Help/rendertiddler": {
            "title": "$:/language/Help/rendertiddler",
            "description": "Render an individual tiddler as a specified ContentType",
            "text": "(Note: The `--rendertiddler` command is deprecated in favour of the new, more flexible `--render` command)\n\nRender an individual tiddler as a specified ContentType, defaulting to `text/html` and save it to the specified filename.\n\nOptionally the title of a template tiddler can be specified, in which case the template tiddler is rendered with the \"currentTiddler\" variable set to the tiddler that is being rendered (the first parameter value).\n\nA name and value for an additional variable may optionally also be specified.\n\n```\n--rendertiddler <title> <filename> [<type>] [<template>] [<name>] [<value>]\n```\n\nBy default, the filename is resolved relative to the `output` subdirectory of the edition directory. The `--output` command can be used to direct output to a different directory.\n\nAny missing directories in the path to the filename are automatically created.\n\nFor example, the following command saves all tiddlers matching the filter `[tag[done]]` to a JSON file titled `output.json` by employing the core template `$:/core/templates/exporters/JsonFile`.\n\n```\n--rendertiddler \"$:/core/templates/exporters/JsonFile\" output.json text/plain \"\" exportFilter \"[tag[done]]\"\n```\n"
        },

        "$:/language/Help/server": {
            "title": "$:/language/Help/server",
            "description": "Provides an HTTP server interface to TiddlyWiki",
            "text": "The server built in to TiddlyWiki5 is very simple. Although compatible with TiddlyWeb it doesn't support many of the features needed for robust Internet-facing usage.\n\nAt the root, it serves a rendering of a specified tiddler. Away from the root, it serves individual tiddlers encoded in JSON, and supports the basic HTTP operations for `GET`, `PUT` and `DELETE`.\n\n```\n--server <port> <roottiddler> <rendertype> <servetype> <username> <password> <host> <pathprefix>\n```\n\nThe parameters are:\n\n* ''port'' - port number on which to listen; non-numeric values are interpreted as a system environment variable from which the port number is extracted (defaults to \"8080\")\n* ''roottiddler'' - the tiddler to serve at the root (defaults to \"$:/core/save/all\")\n* ''rendertype'' - the content type to which the root tiddler should be rendered (defaults to \"text/plain\")\n* ''servetype'' - the content type with which the root tiddler should be served (defaults to \"text/html\")\n* ''username'' - the default username for signing edits\n* ''password'' - optional password for basic authentication\n* ''host'' - optional hostname to serve from (defaults to \"127.0.0.1\" aka \"localhost\")\n* ''pathprefix'' - optional prefix for paths\n\nIf the password parameter is specified then the browser will prompt the user for the username and password. Note that the password is transmitted in plain text so this implementation isn't suitable for general use.\n\nFor example:\n\n```\n--server 8080 $:/core/save/all text/plain text/html MyUserName passw0rd\n```\n\nThe username and password can be specified as empty strings if you need to set the hostname or pathprefix and don't want to require a password:\n\n```\n--server 8080 $:/core/save/all text/plain text/html \"\" \"\" 192.168.0.245\n```\n\nTo run multiple TiddlyWiki servers at the same time you'll need to put each one on a different port. It can be useful to use an environment variable to pass the port number to the Node.js process. This example references an environment variable called \"MY_PORT_NUMBER\":\n\n\n```\n--server MY_PORT_NUMBER $:/core/save/all text/plain text/html MyUserName passw0rd\n```\n"
        },
        "$:/language/Help/setfield": {
            "title": "$:/language/Help/setfield",
            "description": "Prepares external tiddlers for use",
            "text": "//Note that this command is experimental and may change or be replaced before being finalised//\n\nSets the specified field of a group of tiddlers to the result of wikifying a template tiddler with the `currentTiddler` variable set to the tiddler.\n\n```\n--setfield <filter> <fieldname> <templatetitle> <rendertype>\n```\n\nThe parameters are:\n\n* ''filter'' - filter identifying the tiddlers to be affected\n* ''fieldname'' - the field to modify (defaults to \"text\")\n* ''templatetitle'' - the tiddler to wikify into the specified field. If blank or missing then the specified field is deleted\n* ''rendertype'' - the text type to render (defaults to \"text/plain\"; \"text/html\" can be used to include HTML tags)\n"

0 : i > 255 ? 255 : i;\n}\n\nfunction clamp_css_float(f) {  // Clamp to float 0.0 .. 1.0.\n  return f < 0 ? 0 : f > 1 ? 1 : f;\n}\n\nfunction parse_css_int(str) {  // int or percentage.\n  if (str[str.length - 1] === '%')\n    return clamp_css_byte(parseFloat(str) / 100 * 255);\n  return clamp_css_byte(parseInt(str));\n}\n\nfunction parse_css_float(str) {  // float or percentage.\n  if (str[str.length - 1] === '%')\n    return clamp_css_float(parseFloat(str) / 100);\n  return clamp_css_float(parseFloat(str));\n}\n\nfunction css_hue_to_rgb(m1, m2, h) {\n  if (h < 0) h += 1;\n  else if (h > 1) h -= 1;\n\n  if (h * 6 < 1) return m1 + (m2 - m1) * h * 6;\n  if (h * 2 < 1) return m2;\n  if (h * 3 < 2) return m1 + (m2 - m1) * (2/3 - h) * 6;\n  return m1;\n}\n\nfunction parseCSSColor(css_str) {\n  // Remove all whitespace, not compliant, but should just be more accepting.\n  var str = css_str.replace(/ /g, '').toLowerCase();\n\n  // Color keywords (and transparent) lookup.\n  if (str in kCSSColorTable) return kCSSColorTable[str].slice();  // dup.\n\n  // #abc and #abc123 syntax.\n  if (str[0] === '#') {\n    if (str.length === 4) {\n      var iv = parseInt(str.substr(1), 16);  // TODO(deanm): Stricter parsing.\n      if (!(iv >= 0 && iv <= 0xfff)) return null;  // Covers NaN.\n      return [((iv & 0xf00) >> 4) | ((iv & 0xf00) >> 8),\n              (iv & 0xf0) | ((iv & 0xf0) >> 4),\n              (iv & 0xf) | ((iv & 0xf) << 4),\n              1];\n    } else if (str.length === 7) {\n      var iv = parseInt(str.substr(1), 16);  // TODO(deanm): Stricter parsing.\n      if (!(iv >= 0 && iv <= 0xffffff)) return null;  // Covers NaN.\n      return [(iv & 0xff0000) >> 16,\n              (iv & 0xff00) >> 8,\n              iv & 0xff,\n              1];\n    }\n\n    return null;\n  }\n\n  var op = str.indexOf('('), ep = str.indexOf(')');\n  if (op !== -1 && ep + 1 === str.length) {\n    var fname = str.substr(0, op);\n    var params = str.substr(op+1, ep-(op+1)).split(',');\n    var alpha = 1;  // To allow case fallthrough.\n    switch (fname) {\n      case 'rgba':\n        if (params.length !== 4) return null;\n        alpha = parse_css_float(params.pop());\n        // Fall through.\n      case 'rgb':\n        if (params.length !== 3) return null;\n        return [parse_css_int(params[0]),\n                parse_css_int(params[1]),\n                parse_css_int(params[2]),\n                alpha];\n      case 'hsla':\n        if (params.length !== 4) return null;\n        alpha = parse_css_float(params.pop());\n        // Fall through.\n      case 'hsl':\n        if (params.length !== 3) return null;\n        var h = (((parseFloat(params[0]) % 360) + 360) % 360) / 360;  // 0             "text": "This plugin provides syntax highlighting of code blocks using v8.8.0 of [[highlight.js|https://github.com/isagalaev/highlight.js]] from Ivan Sagalaev.\n\n! Usage\n\nWhen the plugin is installed it automatically applies highlighting to all codeblocks defined with triple backticks or with the CodeBlockWidget.\n\nThe language can optionally be specified after the opening triple braces:\n\n<$codeblock code=\"\"\"```css\n * { margin: 0; padding: 0; } /* micro reset */\n\nhtml { font-size: 62.5%; }\nbody { font-size: 14px; font-size: 1.4rem; } /* =14px */\nh1   { font-size: 24px; font-size: 2.4rem; } /* =24px */\n```\"\"\"/>\n\nIf no language is specified highlight.js will attempt to automatically detect the language.\n\n! Built-in Language Brushes\n\nThe plugin includes support for the following languages (referred to as \"brushes\" by highlight.js):\n\n* apache\n* bash\n* coffeescript\n* cpp\n* cs\n* css\n* diff\n* http\n* ini\n* java\n* javascript\n* json\n* makefile\n* markdown\n* nginx\n* objectivec\n* perl\n* php\n* python\n* ruby\n* sql\n* xml\n\nYou can also specify the language as a MIME content type (eg `text/html` or `text/css`). The mapping is accomplished via mapping tiddlers whose titles start with `$:/config/HighlightPlugin/TypeMappings/`.\n"

            "text": "This plugin provides a `<$railroad>` widget for generating railroad diagrams as SVG images.\n\nAlternatively, the [[diagram notation|$:/plugins/tiddlywiki/railroad/syntax]] can be stored in a dedicated tiddler with its `type` field set to `text/vnd.tiddlywiki.railroad`, and that tiddler can simply be transcluded to wherever it is needed.\n\nThe plugin is based on [[a library by Tab Atkins|https://github.com/tabatkins/railroad-diagrams]], and has been extended to make it more flexible, including allowing components of a diagram to function as links or be transcluded from other tiddlers.\n"

            "title": "$:/plugins/tiddlywiki/railroad/syntax",
            "created": "20150103184022184",
            "modified": "20150119220342000",
            "text": "The railroad widget uses a special notation to construct the components defined below.\n\n`x` and `y` here stand for any component.\n\nNames (as opposed to quoted strings) are available when a value starts with a letter and contains only letters, digits, underscores, dots and hyphens.\n\n---\n\n; sequence\n: <$railroad text=\"\"\" [\"<-\"] {x} [\"->\"] \"\"\"/>\n* A sequence of components\n* The `<-` and `->` delimiters allow you to force a single component to be treated as a sequence. This is occasionally useful for spacing a diagram out\n\n---\n\n; optional\n: <$railroad text=\"\"\" \"[\" [\":\"] x \"]\" \"\"\"/>\n* A component that can be omitted\n* The colon makes `x` appear straight ahead\n\n---\n\n; repeated\n: <$railroad text=\"\"\" \"{\" x [:\"+\" y] \"}\" \"\"\"/>\n* A list of one or more `x`\n* The `+` suffix adds `y` as a separator between each `x` and the next\n\n---\n\n; optional repeated\n: <$railroad text=\"\"\" \"[{\" [\":\"] x [:\"+\" y] \"}]\" \"\"\"/>\n* An optional list of `x`, i.e. a list of zero or more `x`\n\n---\n\n; choice\n: <$railroad text=\"\"\" \"(\" {[:\":\"] x +\"|\"} \")\" \"\"\"/>\n* A set of alternatives\n* The colon indicates which branch appears straight ahead. By default, it's the first branch\n\n---\n\n; string / terminal\n: <$railroad text={{$:/plugins/tiddlywiki/railroad/syntax-string}}/>\n* A literal or terminal component\n* This follows the normal ~TiddlyWiki rules for quoted strings\n\n---\n\n; nonterminal\n: <$railroad text=\"\"\" (name | \"<\" string \">\") \"\"\"/>\n* A nonterminal component, i.e. the name of another diagram\n\n---\n\n; comment\n: <$railroad text=\"\"\" \"/\" string \"/\" \"\"\"/>\n* A comment\n\n---\n\n; dummy\n: <$railroad text=\"\"\" \"-\" \"\"\"/>\n* The absence of a component\n\n---\n\n; link\n: <$railroad text=\"\"\" \"[[\" x \"|\" (name|string) \"]]\" \"\"\"/>\n* A link to the tiddler title or URI given by the string or name\n\n---\n\n; transclusion\n: <$railroad text=\"\"\" \"{{\" (name|string) \"}}\" \"\"\"/>\n* Treats the content of another tiddler as diagram syntax and transcludes it into the current diagram\n\n---\n\n; arrow pragma\n: <$railroad text=\"\"\" \"\\arrow\" (\"yes\" | \"no\") \"\"\"/>\n* Controls whether repeat paths have an arrow on them\n* Can be toggled on and off in mid-diagram, if desired\n\n---\n\n; debug pragma\n: <$railroad text=\"\"\" \"\\debug\" \"\"\"/>\n* Causes the diagram to display its parse tree\n\n---\n\n; start/end pragma\n: <$railroad text=\"\"\" (\"\\start\" |: \"\\end\") (\"none\" |: \"single\" | \"double\") \"\"\"/>\n* Controls the style of the diagram's startpoint or endpoint\n"
        },

            "text": "The content of the `<$railroad>` widget is ignored.\n\n|!Attribute |!Description |!Default |\n|text |Text in a special notation that defines the diagram's layout |-- |\n|arrow |If set to `no`, repeat paths do not have an arrow on them |`yes` |\n|start |Style of the startpoint: `single`, `double`, `none` |`single` |\n|end |Style of the endpoint: `single`, `double`, `none` |`single` |\n|debug |If set to `yes`, the diagram displays its parse tree |`no` |\n\nThese options can also be specified via pragmas in the diagram notation, or globally via a dictionary tiddler called `$:/config/railroad`:\n\n```\narrow: yes\nstart: single\nend: single\ndebug: no\n```\n"

!About UFO
; [[UFO|About: UFO]]
: This gives an overview of the UFO programming language.

; [[This document|About: This document]]
: Read about what this document is and how to use it.

; [[License|About: License]]
: Standard license information.

; [[Releases|About: Releases]]
: A list of UFO releases.

!Programming in UFO
; [[Tutorial]]
: Follow the sections in order to learn how to program in UFO.

; [[Writing programs|Reference: Writing programs]]
: Each section focuses on a feature of UFO.

; [[Examples]]
: Example UFO programs.

; [[Reference]]
: A complete guide to every [[data type|Reference: Data type]], [[expression|Reference: Expression]], [[operator|Reference: Operator]], and [[namespace|Reference: Namespace]] in UFO.






I wanted to create a language that had all the features I liked of other languages, while trying to avoid characteristics of other languages that I didn't like.

Thus, designing a language that bore any resemblance to any other language was not a design criterion. Certainly, I did want to steal some things from other languages, but I wasn't going into it with the attitude that it //had to resemble language X//.

!Symbols and identifiers
I got the idea for the distinction between symbols and identifiers from several different functional programming languages: namely Lisp, Scheme, Prolog, and Erlang.

Lisp and Scheme both use the single quote operator to create symbols: `'foo`, whereas Prolog and Erlang treat any word that starts with a lower case letter as a symbol: `foo`, whereas variables begin with a capital letter, like `X`.

I feel like Prolog and Erlang got this backwards. This expression seems to make less syntactic sense:

%%%
''N''ame = jeff
%%%

than this one:

%%%
name = ''J''eff
%%%

The second one seems to convey the information //`name` is just a name, any name, it doesn't matter which one//, whereas //`Jeff` is a specific name//. Those are the roles of, respectively, an identifier and a symbolic constant.

!Operators '=' and ':='
I really like the idea of the `Binding` data structure that I invented for UFO. It represents a paring of two values without actually //doing// anything. The `=` operator creates a binding from two values:

%%%
Temperature=0
%%%

In most other programming languages, the `=` operator does //destructive reassignment//, something that should actually be avoided as much as possible. I wanted to provide destructive reassignment in UFO, but I didn't want to use `=` for two reasons: (1) it's already used as the `Binding` operator, and (2) I wanted it to be a little more difficult to type. Several programming languages already use `:=` to mean assignment (or reassignment), so I chose to use that in UFO.

!The Term data type
I stole this idea from Prolog, but I tweaked it and extended it for UFO.

Previous versions of UFO used a lexer and parser that I wrote myself, instead using a lexer/parser tool. The lexer generated a list of tokens, and each token was a `Term`.

For example, for the input string:

%%%
if true then 10; 20 else 30; 40 end
%%%

the token list would be:

%%%
[Reserved{"if"}, Boolean{true}, Reserved{"then"}, Int{10}, Sep{";"}, Int{20}, Reserved{"else"}, Int{30}, Sep{";"}, Int{40}, Reserved{"end"}, EOI{EOI}]
%%%

Each `Term` in that list has a //hidden attribute// that contains the source code location of each lexeme. In one version of UFO I even attached a reference to the //whole input string// as part of the hidden attribute. Keeping the attribute hidden allowed me to view the list of attributes without all the source code noise.

This latest version of UFO uses the [[Antlr|https://www.antlr.org/]] parser tool and as such does not use terms for its lexer tokens. Nevertheless, I like the `Term` type enough that I'm leaving it in the language.

!It's 'loop', not 'for'

The keyword `for` makes sense to experienced programmers, but only because //that's the way it's always been done.// The keyword `for` is used for a looping construct in [[at least 32 mainstream programming languages|https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/For_loop]].

But does that make it the best word for what it does? It's certainly a //good// word for what it does, but it's not immediately obvious to beginners what it does or how it's used.

I wanted to use a word that described literally what it is or what it does: `loop`. Simple and direct.

!Comments

I spent more time trying to decide what characters to use for line comments and block comments than for any other part of UFO. A lot of the lexicographic design choices in UFO were easy to make. Arrays use curly braces `{}` and lists use square brackets `[]`. This was one of the few choices I made that I wanted to resemble what was found in other languages. Furthermore things that resemble or act like arrays also use curly braces, like the hash table `#{}` and set `${}` , and things that resemble or act like lists use square brackets, like the queue `~[]` and stack `$[]`. I used the dollar sign `$` for sets and stacks because it looks like an S.

Reserved words like `if` and `loop` and `fun` seemed pretty obvious to me, too.

What characters to use for comments, on the other hand, is an arbitrary and almost purely an aesthetic choice.

* The hash mark `#` like in a lot of languages? No, a hash mark starts a hash table: `#{}`.
* Double dash `--` like in Haskell and SQL? It's nice, but I want to use that as a decrement operator.
* Double slash `//` like in C++ and Java? No, that's an integer division operator.
* C-style block comments `/*` `*/`? No, I want them to be //much// easier to type than that (typing those characters requires a lot of finger and even //hand// motion).
* Pascal-style block comments `(*` `*)`? Possibly. I like them a lot but I want the block comment & line comment characters to be similar somehow. I don't know what I'd use for a line comment.

Other characters are already in use: `~ % ^ * - _ + = [ ] { } | : " ' < > . , /`.

The only characters I have left are `!`, `@`, `&`, `?`, `\`, and `;`.

* `!` and `?` might become identifier characters.
* `&` requires too much motion to type (it requires a `Shift` //and// it's directly between the left and right hands, but far from the home row).
* `@` is ok but I feel like I might want to use it as an operator.
* That leaves `\` and `;`. One problem with `\` is that it's too easy to miss that key and hit either `Delete` or `Enter`, whereas `;` is quite nicely placed on the keyboard. The biggest problem with `;` is that I really dislike its asymmetry. Colon `:` is pretty but semicolon `;` is not. (Yes, I'm talking nit-picky aesthetics here.) Overall, though, I think we have a winner with `;`. Then for block comments, since the semicolon is not `Shift`ed the second character used for block comments must also not be `Shift`ed.

!The nil value
At first this value was called `nothing`. I like how descriptive the word is and there's no question about what it represents. Even from version 1 of UFO I was using `nothing` as a value.

Then I learned Python, which uses `None` to represent the same kind of value. I wasn't too tempted to change `nothing`, though.

Then I learned Ruby and used it //a lot// professionally. Ruby uses `nil` to represent the same kind of value. I liked how easy it was to type `nil` and how few characters it used.

I was working on arrays in UFO and created this array:

%%%
{nothing, nothing, nothing, nothing, nothing, nothing, nothing, nothing, nothing, nothing} :: Array
%%%

It made me think how much shorter this array would be:

%%%
{nil, nil, nil, nil, nil, nil, nil, nil, nil, nil} :: Array
%%%

I was already considering using `nil`, but this pushed me over the edge. That's when I decided to be kind to myself and other potential UFO programmers and make the change. In UFO version 3 the value `nothing` became the value `nil`.

There was already a //lot// of code written and a //lot// of documentation. Global search & replace reduces the effort of making the change, but it's still risky. Will something get changed that shouldn't get changed? Will anything break? This is why it's important to make decisions like this //very early// in the design process, when a fundamental change like this has a much smaller effect on the existing code and documentation.

!Running
Un-zip the zip file, `cd` into the directory, type `ufo`.

!Define a function
%%%
fun //name//(//params//) = //body// end
%%%

The //body// can be any number of statements. The statement separator is any whitespace.

See: [[Expression: fun]]

!Assignment
Assignment operator: `let x = 0`<br >
Re-assignment operator: `x := x + 1`

See: [[Expression: let]], [[Operator: Assignment]]

!Data structures
* Array `{` ... `}` (0-based)
* Linked list: `[` ... `]`
* Hash table: `#{` ... `}`
* Binding: `x=y` (a binding is a first-class data value)

See: [[Reference: Data type]]

!Defining a class
You can't. UFO is not (yet) object-oriented.

!Library
If you're looking for the extensive class library: there is none because UFO is not (yet) object-oriented. But see the [[namespace reference|Reference: Namespace]] for all the built-in functions that are available.

!Primitive functions
Primitive functions are called using function notation or method notation:

%%%
let a = {A, B, C}
io:showln(array:count(a))  ; function syntax
io:showln(a.count())       ; method syntax
%%%

The method notation works only for functions in namespaces associated with a specific data structure, and the corresponding namespace has the same name. Currently those namespaces are:

* [[Array|Namespace: array]], [[Binding|Namespace: binding]], [[Closure|Namespace: closure]], [[Evaluator|Namespace: evaluator]], [[File|Namespace: file]], [[HashTable|Namespace: hash]], [[Integer|Namespace: integer]], [[List|Namespace: list]], [[Queue|Namespace: queue]], [[Seq|Namespace: seq]], [[Set|Namespace: set]], [[Stack|Namespace: stack]], [[String|Namespace: string]], [[Term|Namespace: term]]

!Conditionals

%%%
if //condition// then //do this// end
if //condition// then //do this// else //do that// end
%%%

See: [[Expression: if]]

!Loops

It's `loop`, not `for`:

%%%
loop x=5 do
  io:displn(x)
end
%%%

Or on one line, no need for statement separators:

%%%
loop x=5 do io:displn(x) end
%%%

The `while` loop:

%%%
let x = 0
while x < 4 do
  io:displn(x)
  x := x + 1
end
%%%

See: [[Expression: loop]], [[Expression: while]]

!More
See the [[Reference]] sections.

!Organization
The menu on the right shows all the sections of the document.

In order to start learning UFO you should read the [[Tutorial]].

Reference information can be found in either the [[data type|Reference: Data type]], [[expression|Reference: Expression]], or [[namespace|Reference: Namespace]] sections.

Details about writing programs for UFO can be found in [[writing programs|Reference: Writing programs]].

!Don't drown in the river
This document is a [[TiddlyWiki|https://tiddlywiki.com/]] file. Using it comfortably might take a bit of practice.

In a TiddlyWiki application such as this one, each page is called a //tiddler//. As this might sound far less humorous in British English (TiddlyWiki's author's native language) than it does in American English (UFO's author's native language), I'll just call them //pages//.

Each page is displayed here in the middle of the window in the //story river//. When you click a link to open a new page it is added to the top of the story river, pushing the other pages downward. It's easy to get lost in all the pages as they accumulate in the story river, so it could be useful to close a page when you're done reading it.

!Make your own edits
If you're reading this from a local copy of this file, then you're free to edit the document all you want and save the changes. Save a copy of your edited document by pressing the red check mark
{{$:/core/images/save-button}}
on the far right of the window. If the icon is not red, then there are no changes to be saved.

If you think your changes are worth being included in the public release, go ahead and submit a pull request on GitHub: https://github.com/ufo-language

!Toggling menus
In the upper left corner is one of two icons, either a chevron:

{{$:/core/images/chevron-left}}

or a menu icon:

{{$:/core/images/menu-button}}

Clicking the icon will toggle the menu on the left-hand side of the window.

A similar action can be done for the information on the right-hand side of the window.






!What is UFO?
UFO is a general purpose programming language focusing on [[functional programming|https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Functional_programming]] but influenced by just about every programming language in existence [//vast exaggeration//], namely (in alphabetical order): BASIC, C, Erlang, Forth, Go, Haskell, MATLAB, ML, Oz, PostScript, Prolog, Python, Ruby, Scheme, and probably a few others. Not COBOL.

!History of the language
This effort began long ago in a galaxy far away when I was in grad school studying programming languages. I went from asking questions like //How hard is it to add feature x to language y?// to asking //How hard is it to create a new language with feature x?// to finally //Do I really want to do this for the rest of my life?//

It turns out that getting a small, custom language running with feature //x// is usually not all that hard. But getting a reasonably complete language working is a challenge. Cuz, y'know, kids these days... they expect so much from their programming languages.

Version 1 of the language was written in Erlang. I used it to teach network theory &  programming to some able-bodied (and -minded) sailors at the US Submarine Base in Groton CT. I did not get to go on a submarine.

Version 2 of the language was written in Modula-3 and wasn't used by anyone^^(*)^^. I abandoned that and started a new version 2.

^^(*)^^ I had //one// student who took an interest in it and used it for a bit. Hardly worth mentioning.

The next version 2 of the language was written in Java. I used it to teach introductory programming to some courageous high school students during a brief summer program at UConn. At least one of them subsequently enrolled at UConn to study computer science.

This is now version 3. I won't fool myself into thinking that anyone will use this language, anywhere, for any reason. But if you do? Hey, cool!

!The name
I chose UFO because it was the only unused name out of a bunch of others that I wanted to use. In fact, even the name UFO was used for a language many years ago, but that whole project seems to be defunct. Unlike that project, in which UFO was an acronym, here I do not use the name as an acronym. //It does not stand for anything.// It's just a name that I chose. It's short, easy to write, easy to say, it makes a nice command prompt:

`UFO>`

and it fits nicely in a square icon.

{{$:/favicon.ico}}

This programming language name delivers on its promises.

!Puns
The author is not a fan of puns in programming languages, the like of which we see a-plenty with languages such as Java and Python. If you base some work off UFO and want to use a pun for its name, I would neither encourage nor discourage you from doing that. My own preference? Just be cold, be soulless, be unimaginative.






Shows the help menu, which is a list of colon commands that are availble.






Displays the status of the project.

As this is currently a pre-release version, any particular problems, issues, and missing features will be listed here.
















































Runs a program file in the evaluator.

; `:r`
: If no file has been run yet, this will open a file input dialog box to let the user choose a file, and that file is run.
: If a file has already been run, this will cause that same file to be re-run.

; `:r filename`
: Runs the contents of the specified file.

!Description
An Array is a fixed-length, random-access collection.

Please take note of the following:

* Accessing any single element of an array is an [[O(1)|Writing programs: Time complexity: Constant]] operation.
* Searching an array for the existence of a value or for a binding key is an [[O(n)|Writing programs: Time complexity: Linear]] operation.
* Changing the size of an array for any reason, either through insertion, deletion, or appending an element, is an [[O(n)|Writing programs: Time complexity: Linear]] operation because it causes a copy of the array to be made.

!Format
%%%
''{'' //elems// ''}''
%%%

Where //elems// is 0 or more values separated by commas.

!!Examples
%%%
UFO> let ary1 = {A, B, C}
UFO> ary1
{A, B, C} :: Array
UFO> let ary2 = {1, 2, 3}
UFO> ary2
{1, 2, 3} :: Array
UFO> {ary1, ary2}
{{A, B, C}, {1, 2, 3}} :: Array
%%%
%%%
UFO> let ary = {A, B, C}
UFO> ary[1]
B :: Symbol
UFO> ary[1] := Z
UFO> ary
{A, Z, C} :: Array
%%%

!See also
* [[Namespace: array]]
* [[Writing programs: Associative collections]]
* [[Writing programs: Collections]]
* [[Writing programs: Element resolution]]






<<explist $(currentTiddler)$>>






!Description
A binding is an association between two values. There is no intrinsic semantic meaning in a binding, which is why it is categorized as a data type and not an expression.

!Format
%%%
//lhs// ''='' //rhs//
%%%

A binding is simply a //carrier of data//, much like an array or list or list pair:

%%%
A = 10 :: Binding
{A, 10} :: Array
[A, 10] :: List
[A | 10] :: List
%%%

Bindings are an important component in [[associative collections|Writing programs: Associative collections]].

!Examples
%%%
UFO> A=10
A=10 :: Binding
%%%

Either side of a binding can be something other than an atomic value:

%%%
UFO> Name = {Jean, Bartik}
Name = {Jean, Bartik} :: Binding
%%%

!See also
* [[Writing programs: Associative collections]]






!Description
The `Boolean` data type has two members:

* `true`
* `false`

!Examples

UFO> true
true :: Boolean
UFO> false
false :: Boolean
%%%

!Description

By nature of its implementation, a hash table does not store its elements in order.

Accessing any entry in the hash table, either through lookup or through assignment, is a [[constant time|Writing programs: Time complexity: Constant]] operation.

There is a special //invariant// that applies to hash tables:

> Two keys that are the same through [[equality|Operator: Equal to]] will always map to the same value in the hash table.

!Format
%%%
''#{'' //bindings// ''}''
%%%

!Example
%%%
UFO> let h = #{A=10, B=20, C=30}
UFO> h[A]
10 :: Integer
UFO> h[B] := 99
UFO> h
#{C=30, B=99, A=10} :: HashTable
%%%

!See also
* [[Writing programs: Associative collections]]






!Description
This data type represents whole numbers.

This type does not represent //all// integers -- only the ones in the range -2^^31^^ to 2^^31^^-1.

A positive integer is a series of digits. A plus `+` sign is not allowed.

A negative integer is a minus sign `-` followed by a series of digits.

The underscore `_` can be used to separate groups of digits. The underscores are not preserved in the displayed number:

%%%
UFO> 1_000_000
1000000 :: Integer
%%%

!See also

* [[Data type: Real]]






!See also
* [[Namespace: file]]






!Description
A List is a variable-length, sequential access collection, implemented as a linked list of //pairs// (sometimes called [[cons cells|https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cons]]).

Most operations on lists have [[linear time complexity|Writing programs: Time complexity: Linear]], with the exceptions being (a) list creation using the [[list:new|Primitive: list:new]] primitive and (b) creation or pattern matching using improper list notation `[x | y]`: both have [[constant time complexity|Writing programs: Time complexity: Constant]].

!!Format

%%%
''['' //elems// '']''
%%%

Where //elems// is 0 or more values separated by commas.

!!Examples
%%%
UFO> let lst1 = [A, B, C]
UFO> lst1
[A, B, C] :: List
UFO> let lst2 = [1, 2, 3]
UFO> lst2
[1, 2, 3] :: List
UFO> [lst1, lst2]
&#91;[A, B, C], [1, 2, 3]] :: List
%%%

!Improper list notation
This notation can be used to:

# create a new list by attaching a value to the front of a list,
# or get the //first// & //rest// of a list through pattern matching,
# or create an improper list (called a //pair//).

!!Format

%%%
''['' //first// ''|'' //rest// '']''
%%%

!!Examples

''1. Creating a new list''

Given some list, a new list can be created by attaching a value to the front of it. This does not affect the existing list.

%%%
UFO> let lst1 = [A, B, C]
UFO> let lst2 = [Z | lst1]
UFO> lst1
[A, B, C] :: List
UFO> lst2
[Z, A, B, C] :: List
%%%

''2. Get the //first// & //rest// through pattern matching''

%%%
UFO> let lst1 = [A, B, C]
UFO> let [f | r] = lst1
UFO> f
A :: Symbol
UFO> r
[B, C] :: List
%%%

The //rest// of a 1-element list is the empty list:

%%%
UFO> let lst1 = [X]
UFO> let [f | r] = lst1
UFO> f
X :: Symbol
UFO> r
[] :: List
%%%

Attempting to match the //first// or //rest// of the empty list causes an error:

%%%
UFO> let [x|y] = []
Exception: 
Binding mis-match: [x | y] / []
%%%

''3. Creating an improper list''

A //proper list// is one whose //rest// value is a `List`.

An //improper list// is one whose //rest// value is //not// a `List`.

This is an improper list, also called a //pair//:

%%%
UFO> [1 | 2]
[1 | 2] :: List
%%%

Pattern matching works normally with an improper list:

%%%
UFO> let lst = [1 | 2]
UFO> let [f | r] = lst
UFO> f
1 :: Integer
UFO> r
2 :: Integer
%%%

''3a. A proper list can be constructed using //improper list// syntax''

%%%
UFO> [A | [B | [C | []]]]
[A, B, C, D]
%%%

%%%
UFO> let a = []
UFO> let b = [2 | a]
UFO> let c = [1 | b]
UFO> a
[] :: List
UFO> b
[2] :: List
UFO> c
[1, 2] :: List%%%
!See also
* [[Namespace: list]]
* [[Writing programs: Associative collections]]
* [[Writing programs: Collections]]
* [[Writing programs: Element resolution]]

!Format

!Examples

!Description
This is a singleton data type that contains one data value: `nil`. It is often used to denote the absence of a meaningful value.

When evaluated by itself at the command line, the value `nil` does not display a value.

!Format
`nil`

!Examples
The type of `nil` is `Nil`:

%%%
UFO> type:name(nil)
Nil :: Symbol
UFO>
%%%

The value `nil` is not displayed in the command shell:

%%%
UFO> nil
UFO>
%%%

The functions in the [[io namespace|Namespace: io]] will display the value `nil`:

%%%
UFO> io:showln(nil)
nil
%%%

The value `nil` will be displayed in the command shell but only if it's part of something else that is displayed:

%%%
UFO> let l = [nil]
UFO> l
[nil] :: List
UFO> list:first(l)
UFO>
%%%

!See also







<<explist $(currentTiddler)$>>

!Format

!Description
A queue is a collection that allows constant-time insertion of elements at the back of the queue, and constant-time removal of elements from the front of the queue. It is known as a //first-in / first-out// (FIFO) data structure.

!Format
%%%
''~['' //elems// '']''
%%%

Where //elems// is 0 or more values separated by commas.

!Examples
%%%
UFO> let q = ~[]
UFO> queue:enq(q, 100)
UFO> queue:enq(q, 200)
UFO> q
~[100, 200] :: Queue
UFO> queue:deq(q)
100 :: Integer
UFO> queue:deq(q)
200 :: Integer
UFO> q
~[] :: Queue
%%%

!Implementation note
Internally, queue nodes are recycled within each queue instance in an effort to increase the efficiency of repeated enqueueing and dequeueing.

!See also
* [[Namespace: queue]]
* [[Writing programs: Collections]]






!Description
This data type represents numbers that are not necessarily whole numbers. These are stored as [[single-precision floating point values|https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Single-precision_floating-point_format]].

A positive real number is a series of digits that contains a decimal point `.`. The number must begin and end with a digit. A leading plus + sign is not allowed.

A negative real number starts with a minus sign `-` followed by a series of digits that contains a decimal point `.`. The number must begin and end with a digit.

The underscore `_` can be used to separate groups of digits. The underscores are not preserved in the displayed number:

%%%
UFO> 1_000.000_5
1000.00048828125 :: Real
%%%

Notice that the fractional part of a `Real` number is sometimes only an approximation. This is a characteristic of the number format used by the computer's internal representation of single-precision floating point values.

Exponential notation is not supported at this time.

!See also

* [[Data type: Integer]]






!Description
This represents a sequence of numbers starting at a //from// value, going up to a //to// value, optionally with an increment //by// value. The //by// value is called the incrementer.

The sequence includes both the starting and ending values //from// and //to//, unless the number of values in the sequence is not an integer multiple of the //by// value, in which case the //to// value will not be included.

The `Seq` type has the benefit that every operation on a sequence takes constant time (except for converting it to another data type), regardless of the number of values that the sequence represents.

!Format
The two operators <tt>[[..|Operator: Sequence]]</tt> and <tt>[[%|Operator: Sequence by]]</tt> are used to create sequences.

%%%
//from// `..` //to//
%%%

%%%
//from// `..` //to// `%` //by//
%%%

!Examples

%%%
UFO> 1..5
1..5 :: Seq
%%%
%%%
UFO> 1..5 % 2
1..5 % 2 :: Seq
UFO> type:convert(it, List)
[1, 3, 5] :: List
%%%


This example shows that this particular //by// value causes the upper limit //to// value to be omitted from the sequence:

%%%
UFO> type:convert(1..5 % 3, List)
[1, 4] :: List
%%%

!See also
* [[Namespace: seq]]
* [[Operator: Sequence]]
* [[Operator: Sequence by]]






!See also
* [[Namespace: serial]]






!Description
A set is a collection that contains one copy of any value placed in it, no matter how many copies of the value are placed in it. By nature of its implementation, a set does not store its elements in order.

Testing for the presence of an element in a set is an [[O(1)|Writing programs: Time complexity: Constant]] operation, as are adding and removing an element from the set.

Note that when a set is displayed, its elements are not necessarily shown in lexicographic order. The order in which the elements are displayed is dependent on the internal workings of the set.

!Format
%%%
''${'' //elems// ''}''
%%%

Where //elems// is 0 or more values separated by commas.

!Example
%%%
UFO> let s = ${}
UFO> set:add(s, 100)
UFO> set:add(s, 200)
UFO> set:contains(s, 100)
true :: Boolean
UFO> set:contains(s, 200)
true :: Boolean
UFO> set:contains(s, 300)
false :: Boolean
%%%

!See also
* [[Namespace: set]]
* [[Writing programs: Collections]]






!Description
A stack is a collection that allows constant-time insertion and removal of elements from the top of the stack. It is known as a //last-in / first-out// (LIFO) data structure.

!Format
%%%
''$['' //elems// '']''
%%%

Where //elems// is 0 or more values separated by commas.

!Examples
%%%
UFO> let s = $[]
UFO> stack:push(s, 100)
UFO> stack:push(s, 200)
UFO> s
$[200, 100] :: Stack
UFO> stack:pop(s)
200 :: Integer
UFO> stack:pop(s)
100 :: Integer
UFO> s
$[] :: Stack
%%%

!See also
* [[Namespace: stack]]
* [[Writing programs: Collections]]






!Description
A string is a group of characters surrounded by double-quotation marks `"`. The UFO evaluator does not attempt to evaluate anything between the quotes.

!Format
%%%
''"'' //characters// ''"''
%%%

Any character can be escaped with a backslash character `\`. Certain escaped characters are converted automatically into their control-code counterpart:

|`\"` |Double quote |
|`\\` |Backslash |
|`\b` |Backspace |
|`\f` |Form feed |
|`\n` |Newline |
|`\r` |Carriage return |
|`\t` |Tab |

Any escaped character that isn't converted into a control code is simply placed in the string in its unescaped form.

!Examples
%%%
UFO> "Hello, World!"
"Hello, World!" :: String
%%%
%%%
UFO> "abc\ndef\nghi"
"abc\ndef" :: String
UFO> io:displn(it)
abc
def
ghi
%%%
%%%
UFO> :e
"abc
def
ghi"

"abc\ndef\nghi" :: String
%%%
%%%
UFO> "\x\y\z"
"xyz" :: String
%%%

!See also
* [[Primitive: io:fmt]]
* [[Primitive: string:fmt]]






!Description
This is an FIFO queue of characters with no bounds restrictions.

Characters written to a `StringBuffer` are appended to the end of the buffer. Characters read from the buffer are taken from the beginning of the buffer.

!Format

!Examples

!See also
* [[Namespace: stringBuffer]]






!Description

A symbol, or //symbolic constant//, is a value that conveys meaning only lexicographically.
!Syntax

A symbol begins with an upper-case letter and is allowed to contain only upper & lower case letters, digits, and the underscore `_`.

!Examples

%%%
UFO> let additiveColors = {Red, Green Blue}
UFO> let subtractiveColors = {Cyan, Magenta, Yellow}
UFO> let gray50 = #{Red=0.5, Green=0.5, Blue=0.5}
%%%
%%%
UFO> let allowedLevels = {Low, Medium, High}
%%%
%%%
UFO> let answer = Yes
%%%

!Identity

Symbols are //interned//, meaning that any two symbols that are equal are actually identical. This makes them ideal hash keys.

%%%
UFO> Abc == Abc
true :: Boolean
UFO> Abc is Abc
true :: Boolean
%%%

!See also







!Description
A term consists of three parts:

# A symbolic name.
# An array of arguments.
# An optional attribute that can be any single value, and it can be hidden or shown.

Note that a hidden attribute is not private data -- it is simply not displayed.

!Format
Without an attribute:

%%%
//name//{//arguments//}
%%%

With a hidden attribute:

%%%
//name//{//arguments//} / //attribute//
%%%

With a visible attribute:

%%%
//name//{//arguments//} % //attribute//
%%%

!Examples
%%%
ABC{123}
%%%
%%%
Temperature{20, Centigrade}
%%%
%%%
Time{15, Milliseconds}
%%%

%%%
UFO> Abc{123}/"This is a hidden attribute"
ABC{123} :: Term
%%%
%%%
UFO> Abc{123}%"This is a visible attribute"
Abc{123}%"This is a visible attribute" :: Term
%%%

!See also
* [[Namespace: term]]






!Description

!Format

!Examples

!See also



















This is an implementation of [[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quicksort]].

%%%
UFO> :e
fun qsort([])     = []
       | ([x|xs]) = qsort(list:accept(xs, fun(y) = y < x end))
                 ++ [x]
                 ++ qsort(list:accept(xs, fun(y) = y >= x end))
end

%%%

First, create a list of randomly ordered numbers:

%%%
UFO> let lst = list:generate(10, fun(x) = rand:int(100) end)
[97, 94, 28, 20, 7, 35, 22, 81, 40, 7] :: List
%%%

Now call `qsort` to sort the list:

%%%
UFO> qsort(lst)
[6, 7, 12, 18, 24, 28, 31, 40, 77, 84] :: List
%%%

!Description
Suppresses the evaluation of any expression.

!Format
%%%
'//expr//'
%%%

!Example

%%%
UFO> '1 + 2'
1 + 2 :: BinaryOperator
%%%
%%%
UFO> 'io:displn("Hello, World!")'
io:displn("Hello, World!") :: Application
%%%

!See also







!Description
Function or method application.

I.e., function call or method call.

!Format
%%%
//abstr//''(''//args//'')''
%%%

Were //abstr// is the //abstraction// to apply to the //arguments//.

The abstraction can be anything that evaluates to a function or method.

!Examples
In this first example the abstraction is the expression `io:displn` and the arguments are `"Hello,"` `" "`, and `"World"`.

%%%
UFO> io:displn("Hello,", " ", "World!")
Hello, World!
%%%

The abstraction can also be an identifier that refers to a function you've defined. If this is the function:

%%%
UFO> fun color(c) = Color=c end
%%%

Then here the abstraction is the identifier `color` and the argument is `Red`:

%%%
UFO> color(Red)
Color=Red :: Binding
%%%

The abstraction can be an actual function. Here an anonymous function is applied to the argument `10`:

%%%
UFO> (fun (x) = x end)(10)
10 :: Integer
%%%

!See also
* [[Expression: fun]]






!Description
The `async` expression evaluates zero or more expressions, each in an asynchronous thread.  It returns immediately with an array containing the threads.

!Format
%%%
''async'' //statements// ''end''
%%%
Inner statements must be separated by spaces.

!Example

%%%
UFO> let threads = ''async'' 10 20 ''end''
UFO> threads
{Evaluator{1, []}, Evaluator{2, []}} :: Array
UFO> thread:value(threads[0])
10 :: Integer
UFO> thread:value(threads[1])
20 :: Integer
%%%

!Named threads
If a thread expression is a [[binding|Data type: Binding]] and the binding key is an [[identifier|Expression: Identifier]], then the thread is bound to the identifier in the environment. This is done for all named threads before any thread is spawned. Thus, all thread names are available within the environments of all spawned threads.

%%%
UFO> let threads = ''async'' x=do thread:sleep(1000) 123 end y=thread:value(x) ''end''
%%%
The first thread `x` sleeps for 1 second and then returns the value 123. The second thread `y` waits for the final value of the first thread, then returns it.

Wait at least 1 second, then you can get the value of the second thread:

%%%
UFO> thread:value(threads[1])
123 :: Integer
%%%

!See also
''Topics:''

* [[Concurrency|Writing programs: Concurrency]]

''Expressions:''

* [[cobegin|Expression: cobegin]]
* [[nondet|Expression: nondet]]

''Namespaces:''

* [[thread|Namespace: thread]]






!Description
The `cobegin` expression evaluates zero or more expressions, each in an asynchronous thread. It returns only when all threads are finished, and it returns an array containing the final value of each thread.

!Format
%%%
''cobegin'' //statements// ''end''
%%%
Inner statements must be separated by spaces.

!Example
%%%
UFO> ''cobegin'' 10 20 30 ''end''
it = {10, 20, 30} :: Array
%%%

!Named threads
If a thread expression is a [[binding|Data type: Binding]] and the binding key is an [[identifier|Expression: Identifier]], then the thread is bound to the identifier in the environment. This is done for all named threads before any thread is spawned. Thus, all thread names are available within the environments of all spawned threads.

%%%
UFO> ''cobegin'' x=do thread:sleep(1000) 123 end y=thread:value(x) ''end''
{123, 123} :: Array
%%%
The first thread `x` sleeps for 1 second and then returns the value 123. The second thread `y` waits for the final value of the thread named `x`, then returns it.

!See also
''Topics:''

* [[Concurrency|Writing programs: Concurrency]]

''Expressions:''

* [[async|Expression: async]]
* [[nondet|Expression: nondet]]

''Primitives:''

* [[thread:spawn|Primitive: thread:spawn]]






!Description
Executes zero or more statements in sequence in a new environment context.

!Format
%%%
''do'' //statements// ''end''
%%%
Inner statements must be separated by spaces.

!Examples
%%%
UFO> do io:showln(Hello) io:showln(World) end
Hello
World
%%%

!See also







!Description
Defines a named or anonymous function.

!Format
Named:

%%%
''fun'' //ident//''(''//params//'') ='' //statements// ''end''
%%%

%%%
''fun'' //ident//''(''//params//,,1,,'') ='' //statements//,,1,,
 ''|       (''//params//,,2,,'') ='' //statemtnts//,,2,,
 ''|       ...
end''
%%%

Anonymous:

%%%
''fun'' ''('' //params// '') ='' //statements// ''end''
%%%

%%%
''fun (''//params//,,1,,'') ='' //statements//,,1,,
 ''|  (''//params//,,2,,'') ='' //statemtnts//,,2,,
 ''|  ...
end''
%%%

!Examples

''Named function''

%%%
UFO> ''fun f(x) = io:displn("x is ", x) end''
UFO> f(Hello)
x is Hello
%%%

''Anonymous function''

%%%
UFO> let lst = [A, B, C]
UFO> list:apply(lst, ''fun(x) = io:displn("x is ", x) end'')
x is A
x is B
x is C
%%%

A named function is semantically equivalent to an anonymous function with a `let` expression:

%%%
UFO> ''fun f1() = nil end''
UFO> ''let f2 = fun() = nil end''
UFO> f1
fun() = nil end :: Closure
UFO> f2
fun() = nil end :: Closure
%%%

''Using pattern matching''

%%%
UFO> ''fun f({a, b}) = a + b end''
UFO> let ary = {10, 20}
UFO> f(ary)
30 :: Integer
%%%

''Using typed parameters''

%%%
UFO> ''fun f(x :: Integer) = x end''
UFO> f(10)
10 :: Integer
UFO> f(X)
Exception:
Parameter/argument mismatch: [x :: Integer] / [A]
%%%

''Using multiple rules''

%%%
''fun f([x, y]) = f(x) + f(y)
 |   ({x, y}) = f(x) * f(y)
 |   (z) = z
end''
%%%

%%%
UFO> f([1, {2, 3}])
7 :: Integer
%%%

!See also
* [[Writing programs: Pattern matching]]
* [[Writing programs: Recursion and tail recursion]]






!Description
An identifier is a single word that beings with a lower case letter, or possibly an underscore. Subsequent characters may be any number of lower case letters, upper case letters, digits, or the underscore.

In other programming languages these things are usually referred to as //variables//. But technically speaking, a variable is a memory location referred to by an identifier.

%%%
let x = 0
%%%

In that example `x` is an identifier. It refers to a memory location where 0 is stored. It wouldn't be wrong to call `x` a variable because its value can be changed using an assignment operator `:=`.

An identifier can be //quoted// using the [[quote expression|Expression: ' ' (quote)]], thereby suppressing its evaluation, resulting in the identifier itself:

%%%
UFO> 'a'
a :: Identifier
%%%

That value is a name that could refer to a variable, or maybe a function. But `a` is neither a variable nor a function. //It is an identifier.//

An identifier is considered to be an expression because when it is evaluated, it becomes something else: the value associated with that identifier in the current environment.

!Format
The [[BNF notation|https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Backus%E2%80%93Naur_form]] for an identifier would be this:

%%%
[a-z_] [a-zA-Z0-9_]*
%%%

Which is the lexer definition of an identifier: A single word that beings with a lower case letter or underscore. Subsequent characters may be any number lower case letters, upper case letters, digits, or the underscore.

!Anonymous identifiers
Any identifier that begins with an underscore, including just the underscore itself, is an //anonymous identifier//. You can read more about it [[here|Writing programs: Anonymous identifier]].

!Examples
These are all legal identifiers:

%%%
a, b, c, x, y, z
one, two, three
thisIsALongIdentifier
this_is_also_a_long_identifier
%%%

These are examples of anonymous identifiers:

%%%
_, _x, _restOfList
%%%

!See also
* [[Expression: let]]
* [[Expression: let/in]]
* [[Operator: Assignment]]
* [[Writing programs: Anonymous identifier]]






!Description

The `if/then` expression evaluates an expression conditionally.

The `if/then/else` expression evaluates one of two expressions.

!Format
%%%
''if'' //condition// ''then'' //consequent// ''end''
%%%
%%%
''if'' //condition// ''then'' //consequent// ''else'' //alternate// ''end''
%%%

Where:

* //condition// is any expression. It is treated as a [[boolean equivalent|Writing programs: Boolean equivalence]] value.
* //consequent// and //alternate// can be any sequence of statements separated by spaces.

!Examples
%%%
UFO> if true then 100 end
it = 100 :: Integer
%%%

If the condition of an `if`/`then` expression is `false`, then `nil` is returned.

%%%
UFO> if false then 100 end
it = nil :: Nil
%%%
%%%
UFO> if false then 100 else 200 end
it = 200 :: Integer
%%%

!See also
* [[Data type: Boolean]]
* [[Writing programs: Boolean equivalence]]






!Description
Adds one or more bindings to the current environment.

!Format
%%%
''let'' //bindings//
%%%

Where //bindings// are separated by commas.

!Examples
%%%
UFO> let x=10, y=20
UFO> x + y
30 :: Integer
%%%

Non-atomic values can be used on the left-hand side of the binding. Any identifiers will be bound according to the patterns matched:

%%%
UFO> let {a, b} = {10, 20}
UFO> a
10 :: Integer
UFO> b
20 :: Integer
%%%
%%%
UFO> let [first | rest] = [1, 2, 3]
UFO> first
1 :: Integer
UFO> rest
[2, 3] :: List
%%%

!See also
* [[Expression: let/in]]
* [[Writing programs: Pattern matching]]






!Description
Binds values to names (identifiers) in a scoped environment. Any identifiers bound by the `let/in` expression become unbound (or revert to their previous values) after the `let/in` expression finishes.

!Format
%%%
''let'' //bindings// ''in'' //statements// ''end''
%%%
Where //bindings// are separated by commas, and //statements// are separated by spaces.

!Examples
%%%
UFO> let x = 99, y=100
UFO> let x=10, y=20 in x + y end
30 :: Integer
UFO> x
99 :: Integer
UFO> y
100 :: Integer
%%%

Non-atomic values can be used on the left-hand side of the binding. Any identifiers will be bound according to the patterns matched:

%%%
UFO> let {a, b} = {10, 20} in a + b end
30 :: Integer
%%%
%%%
UFO> let [first | rest] = [1, 2, 3] in {First=first, Rest=rest} end
{First=1, Rest=[2, 3]} :: Array
%%%

!See also
* [[Expression: let]]
* [[Writing programs: Pattern matching]]






!Description
Counted iteration expression.

!Format
%%%
''loop'' //iterExpr// ''do'' //statements// ''end''
%%%

Where //iterExpr// is one of:

* An [[integer|Data type: Integer]]: The integer //n// is converted into a [[seq|Data type: Seq]] of the form `0..(n-1)`. The loop iterates over that sequence.
* A [[collection|Data type: Collection]]: the loop iterates once for each element in the collection.
* A [[binding|Data type: Binding]]: The loop iterates once for each element in the //value// half of the binding, assigning each value to the identifier(s) found in the //key// half of the binding.
* Any other [[atomic value|Data type: Atomic]]: The atomic value is treated as if it were a list containing just that one value.

Inner statements must be separated by spaces.

!Examples
Using an integer:

%%%
UFO> loop 4 do io:showln(Hello) end
Hello
Hello
Hello
Hello
%%%

Using a binding:

%%%
UFO> loop x = 4 do io:showln(x) end
0
1
2
3
%%%

Using a sequence:

%%%
UFO> loop n = 1..5 do io:showln(n) end
1
2
3
4
5
%%%

Using an array:

%%%
UFO> loop s = {A, B, C} do io:showln(s) end
A
B
C
%%%

Using a list:

%%%
UFO> loop s = [A, B, C] do io:showln(s) end
A
B
C
%%%

Using an atomic value:

%%%
UFO> loop e = X do io:showln(e) end
X
%%%

!See also
* [[Expression: while]]






!Description
The match expression does pattern matching over its argument expression to select one of its rules. If a rule matches, any identifiers in the pattern are bound to values in the argument expression and the consequent expression is evaluated. If no rule matches the 'else' expression is evaluated if present.

!Format
%%%
''match'' //arg// ''in'' //pattern//,,1,, ''='' //statements//,,1,, ''end''
%%%
%%%
''match'' //arg// ''in'' //pattern//,,1,, ''='' //statements//,,1,, ''else'' //statements// ''end''
%%%
%%%
''match'' //arg//
''in'' //pattern,,1,,// ''='' //statements,,1,,//
 ''|'' //pattern,,2,,// ''='' //statements,,2,,//
 ''|'' ...
''end''
%%%
%%%
''match'' //arg//
''in'' //pattern,,1,,// ''='' //statements,,1,,//
 ''|'' //pattern,,2,,// ''='' //statements,,2,,//
 ''|'' ...
''else''
  //statements//
''end''
%%%

!Examples

%%%
UFO> match 1 in 1=One | 2=Two end
One :: Symbol
%%%
%%%
UFO> match 2 in 1=One | 2=Two end
Two :: Symbol
%%%

A match failure causes an exception to be thrown:

%%%
UFO> match 3 in 1=One | 2=Two end
║ Error: MatchFailure
║   Pattern  : 1
║   Or       : 2
║   Argument : 3
%%%

The `else` clause can be used to supply alternate statements in the case of a match failure:

%%%
UFO> match 3 in 1=One | 2=Two else Other end
Other :: Symbol
%%%

A longer example:

%%%
UFO> :e
loop s = [A, B, C, D] do
  match s
    in A = io:displn("This is rule A")
     | B = io:displn("This is rule B")
     | C = io:displn("This is rule C")
  else
    io:displn("Unknown value: ", s)
  end
end

This is rule A
This is rule B
This is rule C
Unknown value: D
%%%

Pattern matching over data structures can also be done:

%%%
UFO> :e
loop s = [{A, B}, {C}, [D|E], [F], 123] do
  match s
    in {x}    = io:displn("Singleton array with ", x)
     | {x, y} = io:displn("Array pair with ", x, " and ", y)
     | [x]    = io:displn("Singleton list with ", x)
     | [x|y]  = io:displn("List pair with ", x, " and ", y)
  else
    io:displn("Unknown value: ", s)
  end
end

Array pair with A and B
Singleton array with C
List pair with D and E
Singleton list with F
Unknown value: 123
%%%

!See also
* [[Expression: fun]]
* [[Expression: let]]
* [[Expression: let/in]]
* [[Writing programs: Pattern matching]]






!Description
Evaluates multiple expressions, each in a concurrent thread, returning the value of the first expression to finish being evaluated.

!Format
%%%
''nondet'' //statements// ''end''
%%%
Inner statements must be separated by spaces.

!Examples
%%%
UFO> ''nondet'' do thread:sleep(rand:int(100)) A end do thread:sleep(rand:int(100)) B end ''end''
A :: Symbol

UFO> ''nondet'' do thread:sleep(rand:int(100)) A end do thread:sleep(rand:int(100)) B end ''end''
B :: Symbol
%%%

!Named threads
If a thread expression is a [[binding|Data type: Binding]] and the binding key is an [[identifier|Expression: Identifier]], then the thread is bound to the identifier in the environment. This is done for all named threads before any thread is spawned. Thus, all thread names are available within the environments of all spawned threads.

%%%
UFO> ''nondet'' x=100 y=200 ''end''
200
%%%
(//Better example needed.//)

!See also
''Topics:''

* [[Concurrency|Writing programs: Concurrency]]

''Expressions:''

* [[async|Expression: async]]
* [[cobegin|Expression: cobegin]]

''Primitives:''

* [[thread:spawn|Primitive: thread:spawn]]






!Description
Retrieves and returns a value from a collection, or (''TODO: need examples'') allows assignment of a value in a collection.

!Format
%%%
//collection//''[''//index//'']''
%%%

!Examples

''Array''

Array subscripting works with integer indexes or with non-integer keys, just like [[Primitive: array:get]].

%%%
UFO> let a = {A=10, B=20, C=30}
UFO> a[0]
A=10 :: Binding
%%%

Be aware that using an array as an associative collection is a [[linear time|Writing programs: Time complexity: Linear]] operation:

%%%
UFO> a[B]
20 :: Integer
%%%

''Binding''

Using integer indexes 0 or 1 return the //key// or //value//, respectively. Otherwise, using the binding's //key// as the index returns the //value//.

%%%
UFO> let b = X=100
UFO> b[0]
X :: Symbol
UFO> b[1]
100 :: Integer
%%%
%%%
UFO> b[X]
100 :: Integer
%%%

''HashTable''

Owing to the nature of hash tables, subscripting is by associative key only. Integer indexing is not supported.

%%%
UFO> let h = #{A=10, B=20, C=30}
UFO> h[A]
10 :: Integer
%%%

''List''

List subscripting works with integer indexes or with non-integer keys, just like [[Primitive: list:get]].

Be aware that subscripting a list is a [[linear time|Writing programs: Time complexity: Linear]] operation:

%%%
UFO> let lst = [A=10, B=20, C=30]
UFO> lst[1]
B=20 :: Binding
%%%
%%%
UFO> lst[B]
20 :: Integer
%%%

''Seq''

Subscripting a `Seq` works only with integers.

This is a [[constant time|Writing programs: Time complexity: Constant]] operation.

%%%
UFO> let r = 1:10:2
UFO> r :> Array
{1, 3, 5, 7, 9} :: Array
UFO> r[0]
1 :: Integer
UFO> r[4]
9 :: Integer
%%%

''String''

Subscripting a `String` works only with integers.

%%%
UFO> let s = "Hello"
UFO> s[0]
"H" :: String
%%%

''Term''

Term subscripting works with integer indexes or with non-integer keys, just like [[Primitive: term:get]].

The subscripting is performed on the term's arguments.

%%%
UFO> let t = Abc{X=10, Y=20, Z=30}
UFO> t[0]
X=10 :: Binding
%%%

Be aware that using a term as an associative collection is a [[linear time|Writing programs: Time complexity: Linear]] operation:

%%%
UFO> t[Y]
20 :: Integer
%%%

!See also
* [[: (colon)|Operator: Colon]]
* [[Writing programs: Associative collections]]
* [[Writing programs: Element resolution]]






!Description

!Format
%%%
''try'' //statements// ''catch'' //matchRules// ''end''
%%%
%%%
''try'' //statements// ''finally'' //statements// ''end''
%%%
%%%
''try'' //statements// ''catch'' //matchRules// ''finally'' //statements// ''end''
%%%

Where //statements// are separated by spaces, and where //matchRules// is:

%%%
//pattern//,,1,, ''='' //statements//,,1,, ''|'' //pattern//,,2,, ''='' //statements//,,2,, | ...
%%%

The final value of the entire `try`...`end` expression is either:

# The value of the final statement in the `try` clause if no exception is thrown or if no `catch` rules are present.
# The value of the first //matchRule// that matches the exception that is thrown.
# If no //matchRule// matches the exception, then an `UncaughException` is thrown.

The `finally` clause is evaluated whether or not an exception is thrown in the //try// clause. Its final value is ignored.

!Examples

%%%
UFO> try A catch B = C | D = E end
A :: Symbol
%%%
%%%
UFO> try A catch B = C | D = E finally io:displn("Evaluating finally") end
Evaluating finally
A :: Symbol
%%%
%%%
UFO> try throw(B) catch B = C | D = E end
C :: Symbol
%%%
%%%
UFO> try throw(B) catch B = C | D = E finally io:displn("Evaluating finally") end
Evaluating finally
C :: Symbol
%%%
%%%
UFO> try throw(D) catch B = C | D = E end
E :: Symbol
%%%
%%%
UFO> try throw(X) catch B = C | D = E end
║ Error: UncaughtException
║   Exception : X
%%%
%%%
UFO> try throw(X) catch B = C | D = E finally io:displn("Evaluating finally") end
Evaluating finally
║ Error: UncaughtException
║   Exception : X
%%%

!See also
* [[Primitive: exn:throw]]
* [[Writing programs: Exceptions]]






!Description
Iterates while a condition is true.

!Format
%%%
''while'' //condition// ''do'' //statements// ''end''
%%%
Inner statements must be separated by spaces.

!Example
%%%
UFO> let x = 4
UFO> let x = 4
UFO> let y = ''while'' x > 0 ''do'' io:showln(x) x := x - 1 ''end''
4
3
2
1
UFO> y
0 :: Integer
%%%

The identifier `y` is used here to demonstrate the the `while` expression returns a final value, which is the final value of the final iteration of the loop.

!See also
* [[Expression: loop]]

!Description
Logical //and// operator.

Truth table for the //and// operator:

| !//p// | !//q// | !//p// and //q// |
| F | F | F |
| F | T | F |
| T | F | F |
| T | T | T |

!Format
%%%
//p// and //q// :: Boolean
%%%

!Examples
%%%
UFO> false and false
false :: Boolean
%%%
%%%
UFO> false and true
false :: Boolean
%%%
%%%
UFO> true and false
false :: Boolean
%%%
%%%
UFO> true and true
true :: Boolean
%%%

!See also
* [[Writing programs: Boolean equivalence]]






<<explist $(currentTiddler)$>>






!Description
Destructively modifies a variable with a new value.

!Format
%%%
//lhs// := //rhs//
%%%

Where //lhs// can be:

* An identifier.
** If the identifier does not exist yet, it is created.
* A subscripted location from an array, hash table, list, or term.
* A colon operator.

The return value is one of these:

* If the //lhs// is an identifier, then the return value is the new value of the identifier.
* If the //lhs// is a subscript operator, then the return value is the collection being subscripted.

!Examples

''Assignment to a variable''

%%%
UFO> let x = 0
UFO> x := x + 1
1 :: Integer
%%%

''Assignment to a subscript''

Given an index, this destructively modifies an element in a collection at the specified location.

%%%
UFO> let a = {10, 20, 30}
UFO> a[1] = 99
{10, 99, 30} :: Array
%%%

%%%
UFO> let lst = [10, 20, 30]
UFO> lst[1] = 99
[10, 99, 30] :: Array
%%%

<<warning-message "Assigning to a subscript in any collection other than `Array` is an [[O(n)|Writing programs: Time complexity: Linear]] operation">>

''Assignment to a binding in an associative collection''

Given a key, this destructively modifies the value of a binding in an associative collection.

%%%
UFO> let h = #{A=10, B=20, C=30}
UFO> h[B] := 99
#{C=30, A=10, B=99} :: HashTable
%%%

%%%
UFO> let lst = [A=10, B=20, C=30]
UFO> lst[B] := 99
[A=10, B=99, C=30] :: List
%%%

<<warning-message "Assigning to a binding key in any collection other than `HashTable` is an [[O(n)|Writing programs: Time complexity: Linear]] operation">>

''Assignment to a colon operator''

Given a key, this destructively modifies the value of a binding in an associative collection.

%%%
UFO> let h = #{}
UFO> h:a := 98
#{a=98} :: HashTable
UFO> h:b := 99
#{a=98, b=99} :: HashTable
UFO> h:a := 0
#{a=0, b=99} :: HashTable
%%%

Use caution, because this works equally well on the bindings in a namespace.

!See also
* [[Writing programs: Associative collections]]
* [[Writing programs: Destructive modification]]






!Description
The colon operator `:` retrieves the value of a key in an indexable collection. This operator does not evaluate the right-hand index expression.

The colon operator is most commonly used to specify a function in a namespace.

!Format
%%%
//obj// : //index// :: any
%%%
!Examples
%%%
UFO> io:show
show(...) :: Primitive
%%%
%%%
UFO> let h = '#{a=10, b=20}'
UFO> h:a
10 :: Integer
UFO> h:b
20 :: Integer
%%%

!See also
* [[Expression: Subscript]]
* [[Operator: Dot]]
* [[Writing programs: Element resolution]]
* [[Writing programs: Functions and methods]]






<<explist $(currentTiddler)$>>






!Description
Divides one number by another. Returns an integer quotient if the divisor divides the dividend an integer number of times, otherwise returns a real number.

!Format
%%%
//dividend// / //divisor//
%%%

!Examples
%%%
UFO> 4 / 2
2 :: Integer
UFO> 5 / 2
2.5 :: Real
UFO> 4.0 / 2
2 :: Integer
UFO> 5.0 / 2
2.5 :: Real
%%%

!See also
* [[Operator: Arithmetic]]
* [[Operator: Divide integer]]
* [[Operator: Modulo]]






!Description
Divides one number by another. Always returns an integer.

!Format
%%%
//dividend// &#47;&#47; //divisor//
%%%

!Examples
%%%
UFO> 4 &#47;&#47; 2
2 :: Integer
UFO> 5 &#47;&#47; 2
2 :: Integer
UFO> 4.0 &#47;&#47; 2
2 :: Integer
UFO> 5.0 &#47;&#47; 2
2 :: Integer
%%%

!See also
* [[Operator: Arithmetic]]
* [[Operator: Divide]]






!Description
The dot operator `.` converts a function into a method bound to a receiver.

A method can be called by supplying the //remaining// arguments (all but the first).

!Format
%%%
//receiver// . //function// :: Method
%%%
!Examples
%%%
UFO> let a = [A, B, C]
UFO> a.reverse
[A, B, C].reverse(lst :: List) :: Method
UFO> a.reverse()
[C, B, A] :: List
%%%

!See also
* [[Expression: Subscript]]
* [[Operator: Colon]]
* [[Writing programs: Element resolution]]
* [[Writing programs: Functions and methods]]






!Description
Compare two values for equality.

Be aware that comparison of different data types for equality have different time complexities:

|!Type |!Time complexity |
|''Atomic'' |<|
|Boolean |[[O(1)|Writing programs: Time complexity: Constant]] |
|Integer |[[O(1)|Writing programs: Time complexity: Constant]] |
|Nil |[[O(1)|Writing programs: Time complexity: Constant]] |
|Real |[[O(1)|Writing programs: Time complexity: Constant]] |
|String |[[O(n)|Writing programs: Time complexity: Linear]] |
|Symbol |[[O(1)|Writing programs: Time complexity: Constant]] |
|''Collection''^^(*)^^ |<|
|Array |[[O(n)|Writing programs: Time complexity: Linear]] |
|Binding |[[O(1)|Writing programs: Time complexity: Constant]] |
|HashTable |[[O(n)|Writing programs: Time complexity: Linear]] |
|List |[[O(n)|Writing programs: Time complexity: Linear]] |
|Queue |[[O(n)|Writing programs: Time complexity: Linear]] |
|Seq |[[O(1)|Writing programs: Time complexity: Constant]] |
|Set |[[O(n)|Writing programs: Time complexity: Linear]] |
|Stack |[[O(n)|Writing programs: Time complexity: Linear]] |
|Term |[[O(n)|Writing programs: Time complexity: Linear]] |

^^(*)^^ Also be aware that the time complexities shown are for //simple// collections that do not contain other collections. If you were to compare, for example, a //list of lists//, then the time complexity could actually approach [[quadratic|Writing programs: Time complexity: Quadratic]].

!Format
%%%
//lhs// == //rhs// :: Boolean
%%%

!Examples
%%%
UFO> Abc == Abc
true :: Boolean
%%%
%%%
UFO> "Abc" == "Abc"
true :: Boolean
%%%
%%%
UFO> "Abc" == Abc
false :: Boolean
%%%
%%%
UFO> 1 + 1 == 2
true :: Boolean
%%%
%%%
UFO> [A, B, C] == [A, B, C]
true :: Boolean
%%%

!See also
* [[Operator: Is]]
* [[Writing programs: Equality vs. identity]]






!Description
Check of one value is greater than another.

This operator can be used with any two objects that are [[comparable|Writing programs: Comparing values]].

!Format
%%%
//lhs// > //rhs// :: Boolean
%%%

!Examples
%%%
UFO> 2 > 1
true :: Boolean
%%%
%%%
UFO> 4 > 4
false :: Boolean
%%%
%%%
UFO> B > A
true :: Boolean
%%%
%%%
UFO> "abc" > "abcd"
false :: Boolean
%%%

* [[Operator: Comparison]]

!Description
Checks the identity of two objects.

Two objects are identical if they refer to the same object (where //same object// means that they occupy the same place in memory).

!Format
%%%
//obj1// is //obj2// :: Boolean
%%%

!Examples
%%%
UFO> Abc is Abc
true :: Boolean
%%%

%%%
UFO> "abc" is "abc"
false :: Boolean
%%%

%%%
UFO> let x = [1, 2, 3, 4]
UFO> let y = x
UFO> x is y
true :: Boolean
UFO> let z = [1, 2, 3, 4]
UFO> x is z
false :: Boolean
%%%

!See also
* [[Operator: Equal to]]
* [[Operator: Is not]]
* [[Writing programs: Equality vs. identity]]






!Description
Checks if two objects are not identical. This is the logical opposite of the [[is|Operator: Is]] operator.

Two objects are identical if they refer to the same object (where //same object// means that they occupy the same place in memory).

!Format
%%%
//obj1// isnot //obj2// :: Boolean
%%%

!Examples
%%%
UFO> Abc isnot Abc
false :: Boolean
%%%

%%%
UFO> let x = 10
UFO> x isnot nil
true :: Boolean
%%%

%%%
UFO> "abc" is "def"
true :: Boolean
%%%

!See also
* [[Operator: Equal to]]
* [[Operator: Is]]






!Description
Joins two collections into a longer collection. The type of the longer collection is the same as the collection on the left-hand side. The original two collections are unchanged.

!Format
%%%
//lhs// ++ //rhs//
%%%

!Examples
%%%
UFO> [A, B] ++ [C, D]
[A, B, C, D] :: List
%%%
%%%
UFO> {1, 2} ++ [3, 4]
{1, 2, 3, 4} :: Array
%%%
%%%
UFO> let x = Letters{A, B}, y = [C, D], z = {E, F}
UFO> x ++ y ++ z
Letters{A, B, C, D, E, F} :: Term
UFO> x
Letters{A, B} :: Term
UFO> y
[C, D] :: List
UFO> z
{E, F} :: Array
%%%

!See also

!Description
Returns the difference between two numbers.

If both numbers are integers, then the difference will be an integer. If either number is a real number, then the difference will be a real number.

!Format
%%%
//lhs// - //rhs//
%%%

!Examples
%%%
UFO> 6 - 5
1 :: Integer
%%%
%%%
UFO> 6.0 - 5
1.0 :: Integer
%%%

!See also
* [[Operator: Arithmetic]]






!Description
Returns the remainder after dividing one number by another.

If both numbers are integers, then the remainder will be an integer. If either number is a real number, then the remainder will be a real number.

!Format

//lhs// % //rhs//
%%%

!Examples
%%%
UFO> 4 % 3
1 :: Integer
UFO> 4.0 / 3

!Description
Logical inversion.

| !//p// | !not //p// |
| F | T |
| T | F |

!Format

%%%
%%%

true :: Boolean
%%%
