An identifier that starts with an underscore is //anonymous//. That means that it will not be defined anywhere it's used. These are some valid anonymous identifiers:

%%%
_
_x
_ignoreThis
%%%

!Use case
Consider this recursive function:

%%%
fun repeat(0, doSomething) = nil
        | (n, doSomething) = doSomething();
                             repeat(n - 1, doSomething)
end
%%%

In the first rule the `doSomething` identifier is not ever used, so there's no need for there to be an actual identifier there: using a real identifier causes UFO to do the work of binding that variable, but in this case it's all for nothing.

The function could be rewritten like this, replacing `doSomething` with the anonymous identifier `_`:

%%%
fun repeat(0, _) = nil
        | (n, doSomething) = doSomething();
                             repeat(n - 1, doSomething)
end
%%%

Another option is to use the `doSomething` name with a `_` prefix. This is still an "anonymous" identifier:

%%%
fun repeat(0, _doSomething) = nil
        | (n, doSomething) = doSomething();
                             repeat(n - 1, doSomething)
end
%%%






An associative collection is one that contains [[bindings|Data type: Binding]], or //mappings// from //key// to //value//.

The [[HashTable|Data type: HashTable]] should be used as the preferred associative collection, as insertion and lookup are both [[constant time|Writing programs: Time complexity: Constant]] operations. Nevertheless, [[Array|Data type: Array]] and [[List|Data type: List]] both support associative lookups.

!Element resolution operators

Both the colon operator `:` and the subscript expression `[]` can be used to retrieve values from associative collections. The two are explained more [[here|Writing programs: Element resolution]].

!Collection keys

Any [[atomic|Data type: Atomic]] value can be used as a key, and the key types can be mixed within the same table:

%%%
#{X=100, "Y"=200, 3=300, 4.4=400}
%%%

Any [[collection|Data type: Collection]] value can also be used as a key but this is not recommended because collection types are mutable, and this can lead to erratic side effects.

!Array

%%%
UFO> let a = {X=10, Y=20}
UFO> a[X]
10 :: Integer
UFO> a[Y]
20 :: Integer
%%%

Time complexity: [[O(n)|Writing programs: Time complexity: Linear]]

!HashTable

%%%
UFO> let a = #{X=10, Y=20}
UFO> a[X]
10 :: Integer
UFO> a[Y]
20 :: Integer
%%%

Time complexity: [[O(1)|Writing programs: Time complexity: Constant]]

!List

%%%
UFO> let a = [X=10, Y=20]
UFO> a[X]
10 :: Integer
UFO> a[Y]
20 :: Integer
%%%

Time complexity: [[O(n)|Writing programs: Time complexity: Linear]]

!See also
* [[Writing programs: Element resolution]]






Every value in UFO has an intrinsic Boolean value, and as such it can be used as the condition of an `if` statement or `while` loop.

Things that are considered to be `false`:

|!Atomic values |<|
|`false` |`Boolean` |
|`0` |`Integer` |
|`nil` |`Nil` |
|`0.0` |`Real` |
|`""` |`String` |
|!Empty collection |<|
|`{}` |`Array` |
|`#{}` |`HashTable` |
|`[]` |`List` |
|`~[]` |`Queue` |
|`${}` |`Set` |
|`$[]` |`Stack` |

Any other value is considered to be `true`.

!Example using 'if'
Any non-empty string is considered to be `true`, while the empty string `""` is considered to be `false`. Here's a small function that demonstrates this:

%%%
fun getName() =
  let name = io:readLine()
  if name then
    io:displn("Hello, ", name)
  else
    io:displn("You didn't enter your name!")
  end
end
%%%

To test this function, call it and then enter either your name or an empty line. If `name` is the empty string, then the condition of the `if` statement evaluates to `false`. If the string is not empty it evaluates to `true`.

!Example using 'while'
This loop iterates as long as the value of `n` is not false. It is false only when its value is 0.

%%%
UFO> let n = 5
UFO> while n do io:showln(n); n := n - 1 end
5
4
3
2
1
%%%

!See also
* [[Data type: Boolean]]
* [[Expression: if]]
* [[Expression: while]]






%%%
class Foo
  x = 0
  fun f(self) = io:displpn("Hello, Foo") end
end
%%%

%%%
UFO> let f1 = Foo()
UFO> f1.foo()
Hello, Foo
%%%






!Collections contain other values
Array, Binding, HashTable, List, Queue, Seq, Set, Stack, Term

!Collections can contain collections







Colon commands are entered in the UFO command shell. They are not part of the UFO language.

%%%
UFO> :?
  :?            show this help
  :cav          lists issues of which the user should be aware
  :d            toggle debug mode
  :e            edit multi-line text (enter blank line when finished)
  :env          show environment
  :eval         show evaluator
  :expr         show expression from last parse
  :os           show the object stack
  :q            quit
  :tb           show traceback from last exception
%%%






Like many programming languages, UFO has two types of comments: line comments and block comments.

!Line comments
The line comment character is `;`. It may appear anywhere on a line, and everything after it is ignored until the end of the line on which it appears.

%%%
; My first program
io:displn("Hello, World!")
%%%

!Block comments
The block comment characters are `;-` and `-;`. Everything that appears between those symbols is ignored.

%%%
;- Function qsort
 | Performs a Quicksort on a list of numbers.
 | Input:
 |   The input must be a List. Best performance is achieved when the
 |   first element in the list is close to the median value of the list.
 | Output:
 |   The return value is a new list with the elements placed in ascending order.
 -;
fun qsort(...) ...
%%%

The use of vertical bars `|` in that comment block is stylistic only.






Only objects having the same type (with some exceptions) can be compared to each other using the relational comparison operators [[<|Operator: Less than]], [[<=|Operator: Less than or equal]], [[>=|Operator: Greater than or equal]], [[>|Operator: Greater than]].

Types that can be compared:

|[[Array|Data type: Array]] |Arrays are compared element-by-element. |
|[[Binding|Data type: Binding]] |Bindings are compared by //key// first, then by //value//. |
|[[Boolean|Data type: Boolean]] |`false` < `true`. |
|[[Integer|Data type: Integer]] |Can be compared to `Integer` or `Real`. |
|[[List|Data type: List]] |Lists are compared element-by-element. |
|[[Nil|Data type: Nil]] |The value `nil` is equal to itself and less than every other value. |
|[[Queue|Data type: Queue]] |Queues are compared element-by-element. |
|[[Real|Data type: Real]] |Can be compared to `Real` or `Integer`. |
|[[Seq|Data type: Seq]] |Sequences are compared by //from// first, then by //to//, then by //by//. |
|[[Set|Data type: Set]] |Sets are compared element-by-element. |
|[[Stack|Data type: Stack]] |Stacks are compared element-by-element. |
|[[String|Data type: String]] |Strings are compared character-by-character. |
|[[Symbol|Data type: Symbol]] |Symbols are compared character-by-character. |
|[[Term|Data type: Term]] |Terms are compared by //name// first, then by //elements//, then by //attribute//. |

!See also
* [[Operator: Comparison]]






Concurrency can be achieved through a number of means:

; The [[async|Expression: async]] expression
: This spawns one or more threads and immediately returns the thread objects in an array.

; The [[cobegin|Expression: cobegin]] expression
: This spawns one or more threads, waits for all of them to complete, and returns all the final values in an array.

; The [[nondet|Expression: nondet]] expression
: This spawns one or more threads and returns the value of the first thread to complete.

; The [[thread|Namespace: thread]] namespace
: Primitives for starting, stopping, and communicating with threads.

At the present moment, a //thread// is the same as an //evaluator//.

!Thread communication
See [[Primitive: thread:send]]






!io:dispString(_) and io:showString(_)
This returns the standard human- and machine-readable form of the value. It returns a string that's the same as how the value would be displayed or shown at the UFO command prompt.

%%%
UFO> let a = {A, B, C}
UFO> io:dispString(a)
"{A, B, C}" :: String
UFO> io:showString(a)
"{A, B, C}" :: String
%%%

!type:convert(_, String)
This joins together the elements of a collection, treating the elements in the collection as characters (or words or substrings) from which to build the string.

%%%
UFO> let a = {A, B, C}
UFO> type:convert(a, String)
"ABC" :: String
%%%






UFO uses strong, dynamic, implicit typing.

* It is //''strong''// because a value of any built-in type in UFO can't be treated as though it were a value of a different type.
* It is //''dynamic''// because type checking occurs at run-time, not at compile time.
* It is //''implicit''// because the programmer is not required to specify any type annotation in a program.






''TODO: discuss the issue here''

Caution must be observed when using primitive functions that perform destructive modification on (or //mutate//) a data structure.

!Mutation of hash keys

Two arrays will be used, one as the key and one as the value:

%%%
UFO> let key = {A}
UFO> let value = {B}
UFO> let h = #{key=value}
UFO> h
#{{A}={B}} :: HashTable
%%%

Let's now change the element inside the `value` array. The change is visible inside the hash table:

%%%
UFO> array:set(value, 0, Z)
{Z} :: Array
UFO> h
#{{A}={Z}} :: HashTable
%%%

There is little danger in changing the value inside a hash table. That's one of the things that the hash table was designed for.

Let's now change the element inside the `key` array. This change is also visible inside the hash table:

%%%
UFO> array:set(key, 0, Q)
{Q} :: Array
UFO> h
#{{Q}={Z}} :: HashTable
%%%

If we use the identical object (meaning, the value of the `key` identifier), then the value can be retrieved:

%%%
UFO> hash:get(h, key)
{Z} :: Array
%%%

However, if we try using the same key that is not the identical value, then the value is not accessible:

%%%
UFO> hash:get(h, {Q})
UFO>
%%%

Truly? Let's be sure:

%%%
UFO> hash:get(h, {Q}, NotFound)
NotFound :: Symbol
%%%

It gets even more confusing if we add a binding with that same key:

%%%
UFO> hash:put(h, {Q}, 123)
#{{Q}={Z}, {Q}=123} :: HashTable
%%%

Even if we try using the original key, the value can't be retrieved:

%%%
UFO> hash:get(h, {A})
UFO>
%%%

Destructive modification of a hash key causes a violation of a hash table invariant: that two keys that are the same should always map to the same value inside the hash table.

!See also
* [[Data type: HashTable]]






The [[io:disp|Primitive: io:disp]] and [[show|Primitive: io:show]] primitives are both used to display information on the screen. The difference is that [[io:disp|Primitive: io:disp]] is intended to generate human-readable output, while [[io:show|Primitive: io:show]] is intended to generate output that is less human-readable and more [[machine readable|https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Machine-readable_data]].

The [[io:disp|Primitive: io:disp]] primitive is most useful for displaying information to a user, while the [[io:show|Primitive: io:show]] primitive is most useful for debugging purposes: it //shows// you what the value of something is.

Currently^^(*)^^ the [[io:disp|Primitive: io:disp]] and [[io:show|Primitive: io:show]] primitives display all data values the same way except for strings.

^^(*)^^ <small>I say //currently// because this may extend to other types in the future.</small>

!Strings
The [[io:disp|Primitive: io:disp]] primitive displays a string without the string's enclosing quotation marks, but [[io:show|Primitive: io:show]] shows the quotation marks.

%%%
UFO> io:disp("Hello, World!")
Hello, World!
UFO> io:show("Hello, World!")
"Hello, World!"
%%%

!Rationale
It's possible for two values having different types to be //displayed// the same:

%%%
UFO> let a1 = true, a2 = "true"
UFO> do io:displn(a1); io:displn(a2) end
true
true
%%%
%%%
UFO> let b1 = Abc, b2 = "Abc"
UFO> do io:displn(b1); io:displn(b2) end
Abc
Abc
%%%

Two values of different types will always be //shown// differently:

%%%
UFO> do io:showln(a1); io:showln(a2) end
true
"true"
%%%
%%%
UFO> do io:showln(b1); io:showln(b2) end
Abc
"Abc"
%%%







There are two element resolution operators: the colon operator `:` and the bracketed subscript expression `[]`. The key distinctions between them are:

* The [[colon expression|Operator: Colon]] uses the RHS (right-hand side) //verbatim// as the key in a collection. The collection is the value of the LHS (left-hand side).
* The [[bracketed subscript expression|Expression: Subscript]] evaluates the value within the brackets, then uses that value as the key in the collection. The collection is the value of the LHS (left-hand side).
* Both the colon expression and subscript expression can be the target of an [[assignment operator|Operator: Assignment]]:
** `x:y := z`
** `x[y] := z`
* The expression `a:b` is equivalent to the expression `a['b']`.

''Colon operator using a Symbol''

Here's a hash table that binds the symbol `A` to the value `100` (recall that a symbol always evaluates to itself):

%%%
UFO> let h = #{A=100}
UFO> h
#{A=100} :: HashTable
%%%

The colon operator can be used to retrieve the value bound to `A` in the table:

%%%
UFO> h:A
100 :: Integer
%%%

The colon operator uses `A` verbatim to look for the value, and it finds the value 100.

''Colon operator using an identifier''

Since the colon operator does not evaluate the RHS, the RHS of can be an identifier:

%%%
UFO> io:displn
%%%

In that expression UFO will evaluate `io`, and then use `displn` verbatim to find the value in that collection.

%%%
UFO> io
#{nl=nl(), fmt=fmt(fmtStr :: String, bindings), showln=showln(...), ...}
%%%

Notice that `displn` is unbound:

%%%
UFO> displn
 ║ UnboundIdentifier
 ║  Identifier : displn
%%

A //namespace// in UFO is just a [[hash table|Data type: HashTable]] that contains [[identifier|Expression: Identifier]] names bound to [[primitive functions|Writing programs: Namespaces and primitives]]. The colon operator is most commonly used to retrieve a primitive from a namespace:

%%%
UFO> io:displn
displn(...) :: Primitive
%%%

This gets the value of `displn` in the hash table bound to `io`:

%%%
UFO> io:displn
displn(...) :: Primitive
%%%

The colon operator works with any hash table, too, not just namespaces:

%%%
UFO> let a = #{}
UFO> a:b := 10
#{b=10} :: HashTable
UFO> a:b
10 :: Integer
%%%

''Bracket expression using a Symbol''

The bracket expression can also be used to retrieve the value bound to `A` in the table:

%%%
UFO> h[A]
100 :: Integer
%%%

The bracket expression first evaluates the expression within the brackets: any symbol evaluates to itself, so `A` evaluates to `A`. The value bound to `A` in the table is `100`.

''Colon operator using an Identifier''

Here's a hash table that binds the //identifier// `a` to the value `100`:

%%%
UFO> let h = #{'a'=100}
UFO> h
#{a=100} :: HashTable
%%%

The colon operator can be used to retrieve the value bound to `A` in the table:

%%%
UFO> h:a
100 :: Integer
%%%

Notice that `a` is not evaluated before it's used. The colon operator uses `a` verbatim to look for the value, and it finds the value 100.

''Subscript expression using an Identifier''

In this case the bracket expression works a little differently:

%%%
UFO> h[a]
Exception:
Unbound identifier: 'a'
%%%

The subscript expression first evaluates the expression within the brackets: the identifier `a` is currently not bound to any value in the environment, so the evaluator issues an error.

If `a` were to have a value bound to it, then that value could be used to look for a binding in the hash table, like this:

%%%
UFO> let h = #{A=100}
UFO> let a = A
UFO> a
A :: Symbol
%%%

Now the identifier `a` is bound to the symbol `A`. Since the symbol `A` is used as a key in the hash table, we can use either the symbol `A` or the value of the identifier `a` to retrieve that value:

%%%
UFO> h:A
100 :: Integer
UFO> h:a
Exception:
Key 'a' not found in collection #{A=100}
%%%

Oops, remember that the colon operator does not evaluate the right hand side, but the subscript operator does!

%%%
UFO> h[A]
100 :: Integer
UFO> h[a]
100 :: Integer
%%%

The expression `h[a]` works only because the identifier `a` evaluates to the symbol `A`.

!See also
* [[Expression: Identifier]]
* [[[] (subscript)|Expression: Subscript]]
* [[: (colon)|Operator: Colon]]
* [[Writing programs: Associative collections]]






!The '==' equality operator
This determines if two values are superficially equal.

; For atoms
: Do the atoms look the same? If they do, then they are equal.

; For collections
: Do the collections have the same type, the same length, and the same elements in the same order? If they do, then they are equal.

!The 'is' identity operator
This determines if two values are the same object, meaning they reside at the same memory location, meaning that they are not two distinct objects but //the very same object//.

Any two values that are //identical// are also //equal//, but not every two values that are //equal// are //identical//.

; Atoms
: Symbols that look the same are identical. This is their purpose.
: The boolean values `true` and `false` are always identically either `true` or `false`.
: The value `nil` is always identical to itself.
: Atomic values of other types may or may not be identical: generally, if they were created separately then they will not be identical.

; Collections
: Any two collections that were created separately will not be identical.

!Examples
%%%
UFO> 1 == 1
true :: Boolean
UFO> 1 is 1
false :: Boolean
%%%
%%%
UFO> true is true
true :: Boolean
UFO> false is false
true :: Boolean
%%%
%%%
UFO> nil is nil
true :: Boolean
%%%
%%%
UFO> [A, B, C] == [A, B, C]
true :: Boolean
UFO> [A, B, C] is [A, B, C]
false :: Boolean
%%%
%%%
UFO> let a = {A, B, C}
UFO> a == {A, B, C}
true :: Boolean
UFO> a is {A, B, C}
false :: Boolean
UFO> a is a
true :: Boolean
%%%

!See also
* [[Operator: Equal to]]
* [[Operator: Is]]






Similar to many other functional programming languages like Scheme, Lisp, ML, and Haskell, every statement in UFO has a value (either a //return value// or //final value//, however you want to think about it). There is no such thing as `void` like there is in C, C++, or Java.

Consider the `if` statement: it returns the value of the //consequent// (the `then` part) or the //alternate// (the `else` part):

%%%
UFO> if true then 100 else 200 end
100 :: Integer
%%%
%%%
UFO> if false then 100 else 200 end
200 :: Integer
%%%

However, you are allowed to construct an `if` statement without an alternate. What happens if the condition is false?

%%%
UFO> if false then 100 end
UFO>
%%%

It seems as though nothing at all happened. But let's evaluate that statement one more time and save its return value in a variable called `res`, and see what that value is:

%%%
UFO> let res = if false then 100 end
UFO> res
UFO>
%%%

It seems that `res` is defined because it didn't show an error, but what's in that variable? There are actually several ways to get that information:

%%%
UFO> io:showln(res)
nil
%%%
%%%
UFO> type:name(res)
Nil :: Symbol
%%%
%%%
UFO> x is nil
true :: Boolean
%%%

This is a special value in the UFO command shell: it won't ever display the value `nil`.

Thus, anything that does not have a meaningful value to return can just return `nil`.

In fact, even the simple `let` expression returns the value `nil`:

%%%
UFO> let res2 = (let x = 0)
UFO> res2 is nil
true :: Boolean
%%%

!Summary

//Everything// in UFO has a value.






!Throwing an exception

The `exn:throw` primtive is used to throw an exception. The exception payload can be any object.

%%%
UFO> exn:throw(Error{"Something went wrong"})
║ Error: UncaughtException
║   Exception : Error{"Something went wrong"}
%%%
%%%
UFO> exn:throw(nil)
║ Error: UncaughtException
║   Exception : nil
%%%

!Catching an exception

The [[try|Expression: try]] expression is used to catch an exception.

%%%
UFO> try exn:throw(nil) catch nil = CaughtNil end
CaughtNil :: Symbol
%%%

!See also
* [[Expression: try]]
* [[Primitive: exn:throw]]






Every function in each namespace (with just a few exceptions) can be called either as a function or as a method.

!Review of the colon operator `:`

The `list` namespace, for example, contains functions that can be called on lists:

%%%
UFO> ''hash:keys(list)''
${accept, get, take, new, setFirst, setRest, reverse, count, first, rest, map, drop, reject, indexOf, contains, dom} :: Set
%%%

The colon operator `:` returns one of the functions from the namespace:

%%%
UFO> ''list:reverse''
reverse(lst :: List) :: Primitive
%%%

A primitive function is called by supplying arguments for the parameters:

%%%
UFO> ''let a = [A, B, C]''
UFO> ''list:reverse(a)''
[C, B, A] :: List
%%%

!Use of the dot operator `.`

The dot operator `.` can be used with an object and a function name (one of the functions from the namespace associated with that object), and it returns a method bound to the receiver:

%%%
UFO> ''a.reverse''
method [A, B, C].reverse(lst :: List) :: Method
%%%

Note that the method shows all the parameters of the primitive function (which is just `(lst :: List)` in this example), even though the first parameter is bound to the receiver and will not need an argument when the method is called.

In other words, when you call a method you must supply arguments for //all but the first parameter//:

%%%
UFO> ''a.reverse()''
[C, B, A] :: List
%%%

!Discouraged methods
Each of the `:new` functions in the data structure namespaces is intended to be used as a function and not a method.

For example, the `list:new` function takes two arguments: the //first// part of the list and the //rest// of the list.

%%%
UFO> ''list:new''
new(first, rest) :: Primitive
UFO> ''list:new(A, B)''
[A | B] :: List
%%%

It is certainly possible to use `.new` as a method, but it will bind the receiver list to the //first// parameter, leaving just the //rest// parameter.

%%%
UFO> ''let lst = [A, B, C]''
UFO> ''lst.new''
method [A, B, C].new(first, rest) :: Method
UFO> ''lst.new(D)''
[[A, B, C] | D] :: List
UFO> ''lst.new([D, E, F])''
[[A, B, C], D, E, F] :: List
%%%

!Non-methods

Namespaces such as `io`, `math`, `namespace`, and `type` have no associated data type, and thus there is no way to convert those functions to methods. These functions will always be used in function form.

!See also
* [[Data type: Method]]
* [[Operator: Colon]]
* [[Operator: Dot]]






!In the command shell
The `let` expression is used to create bindings in the command shell:

%%%
UFO> let x = 10
%%%

Thereafter, the identifier `x` can be used and its value will be 10.

%%%
UFO> x + x
20 :: Integer
%%%

You can use the special `:env` [[colon command|Writing programs: Colon commands]] to see what the current environment is:

%%%
UFO> :env
[x=10]
%%%

It's possible to set `x` to a new value:

%%%
UFO> let x = 15
%%%

Now the value of `x` is 15:

%%%
UFO> x + x
30 :: Integer
%%%

But take a look at the environment again:

%%%
UFO> :env
[x=15, x=10]
%%%

The identifier `x` is bound //twice//! This is a feature, not a bug. Have a look at how the [[let|Expression: let]] expression works:

> //Adds one or more bindings to the current environment.//

Thus, `let` creates a //new// binding instead of changing the value of an //existing// binding (the [[:=|Operator: Assignment]] operator will do that).

!!Why?

Lexical binding has effects that are subtle but very powerful.

With the value of `x` equal to 15, let's define this function:

%%%
UFO> fun show_x() = io:displn("The value of x is ", x) end
%%%

Calling the function shows this information:

%%%
UFO> show_x()
The value of x is 15
%%%

Now bind `x` to a new value. Let's put it back to 10:

%%%
UFO> let x = 10
%%%

But calling `show_x` may not have the effect you expected:

%%%
UFO> show_x()
The value of x is 15
%%%

The `show_x` function has a //lexical environment// attached to it, which contains all the values of all the free variables in the function at the time the function was defined.

Keep reading for even more explanation.

!In functions

Each function you define has a //lexical environment// attached to it. A function's lexical environment is created at the same time the function is defined.

When the function is called, it uses its lexical environment to resolve any free variables. A free variable is any identifier that's not also a parameter.

This function `f` has two free variables, `x` and `y`:

%%%
fun f() = x + y end
%%%

Before defining the function for real, make sure `x` and `y` have values:

%%%
UFO> let x = 10, y = 20
UFO> fun f() = x + y end
UFO> f
fun() = x + y end :: Closure
%%%

The fact that the function is actually a `Closure` means that all //open// (or //free//) variables have been //closed// (or //bound//) in the lexical environment.

Call the function to see its value:

%%%
UFO> f()
30 :: Integer
%%%

When the function is called it gets the values of `x` and `y` from its lexical environment. Unsurprisingly, those values are 10 and 20. Use the `closure:lexEnv` primitive function to see the function's lexical environment:

%%%
UFO> closure:lexEnv(f)
[y=20, x=10] :: List
%%%

To see what the effect the lexical environment has on the function, use the assignment operator `:=` to destructively change the value of `x` in the command shell, and then check `f`'s lexical environment again:

%%%
UFO> x := 99
UFO> x
99 :: Integer
UFO> closure:lexEnv()
[y=20, x=10] :: List
%%%

Although the value of `x` in the command shell has been changed from 10 to 99, in the function `f` the identifier `x` is still bound to 10.

!!Putting it to use
The bindings in the lexical environment can be used like any environment bindings can, meaning they can be used to store //internal state//: a function can use and modify the values in its own lexical environment.

To start, here's a function with one free variable, `x`:

%%%
fun inc() = x := x + 1; x end
%%%

Try to understand how the function works: it increments the value of `x`, then returns that new value of `x`.

In order for this function to work, there needs to be a value for `x` before the function is defined:

%%%
UFO> let x = 0
%%%

Now define the function:

%%%
UFO> fun inc() = x := x + 1; x end
%%%

Calling `inc()` repeatedly shows that the value of `x` in `f`'s lexical environment is being changed:

%%%
UFO> inc()
1 :: Integer
UFO> inc()
2 :: Integer
UFO> inc()
3 :: Integer
%%%

You can use the `closure:lexEnv` primitive again to verify it:

%%%
UFO> closure:lexEnv(inc)
[x=3] :: List
%%%

This value of `x` that the `inc` function is using is held privately in its lexical environment.

!Using a local identifier in a lexical environment
The bound identifier that gets used to build a function's lexical environment can come from anywhere, as long as it's defined in a context where the new function being built can find it.

Here's an example where a function's parameter is used as the identifier to create an inner function's lexical closure:

%%%
fun makeInc(x) =
  fun () = x := x + 1; x end
end
%%%

The function `makeInc` takes one argument and binds it to the identifier `x`. Say we call the `makeInc` function with the argument 0, so its local environment now contains only the one binding `x=0`. The body of `makeInc` creates a new function that has one free variable, `x`, so that inner function's lexical environment will also contain the binding `x=0`. That new function is returned from the `makeInc` function.

%%%
UFO> let i1 = makeInc(0)
UFO> i1
fun() = x := x + 1; x end :: Closure
UFO> UFO> closure:lexEnv(i1)
[x=0] :: List
%%%

The lexical environment `[x=0]` is what the `i1` function will use to resolve the identifier `x`.

%%%
UFO> i1()
1 :: Integer
UFO> i1()
2 :: Integer
%%%

Any new //incrementer// function created using the `makeInc` function will operate independently of any other:

%%%
UFO> let i2 = makeInc(100)
UFO> i2()
101 :: Integer
UFO> i2()
102 :: Integer
UFO> i1()
3 :: Integer
UFO> i1()
%%%






Normally when a function is called the following things happen in this order:

# parameters and arguments are bound together in an environment local to the function,
# the body of the function is evaluated (specifically, the body of the selected rule),
# the value of the final expression in the body is returned to the caller.

The important issue here is that the body of the function is evaluated //every// time the function is called.

!Caching function values

Here's a function (also seen in the [[tutorial|Tutorial 21. Recursion]]) that calculates the sum of the numbers from 1 to //n//:

%%%
fun sum(1) = 1
 |     (n) = n + sum(n - 1)
end
%%%

Run it to see how it works:

%%%
UFO> sum(5)
15 :: Integer
%%%

Here's a version of the same function that displays a call trace as it runs:

%%%
fun sum(1) = io:displn("sum(1) = 1")
             1
 |     (n) = let res = n + sum(n - 1) in
               io:displn("calculated sum(", n, ") = ", res)
               res
             end
end
%%%

Run it:

%%%
UFO> sum(5)
sum(1) = 1
calculated sum(2) = 3
calculated sum(3) = 6
calculated sum(4) = 10
calculated sum(5) = 15
15 :: Integer
%%%

If you call it again you can see that it has to re-do all the same work:

%%%
UFO> sum(5)
sum(1) = 1
calculated sum(2) = 3
calculated sum(3) = 6
calculated sum(4) = 10
calculated sum(5) = 15
15 :: Integer
%%%

Notice that the values are always the same: for example, `sum(4)` is always `10`. This is true of `sum(n)` for all values of `n`.

Another thing to notice is that the number of recursive calls is proportional to `n`:

%%%
UFO> sum(10)
sum(1) = 1
calculated sum(2) = 3
calculated sum(3) = 6
calculated sum(4) = 10
calculated sum(5) = 15
calculated sum(6) = 21
calculated sum(7) = 28
calculated sum(8) = 36
calculated sum(9) = 45
calculated sum(10) = 55
55 :: Integer
%%%

This function exhibits [[linear time complexity|Writing programs: Time complexity: Linear]].

This function also exhibits [[referential transparency|https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Referential_transparency]], which means that a function call and the value of that function call are interchangeable. This is true of all pure functions: a pure function is one that returns the same value when called with the same arguments.

We can take advantage of this property and set up a cache in which to store the sums. When the function is called, check the cache: if the value exists then just return it. Otherwise, calculate the sums:

%%%
let cache = #{}
fun sum(1) = io:displn("sum(1) = 1")
             1
 |     (n) = let res = cache.get(n) in
               if res is nil then
                 res := n + sum(n - 1)
                 io:displn("calculated sum(", n, ") = ", res)
                 cache[n] := res
               end
               ;io:displn("sum(", n, ") = ", res)
               res
             end
end
%%%

When a cache like this is used to store the return values of a function, we say that the function is //memoized//.

The first time the function is called, the //memo cache// is empty so it must calculate each sum:

%%%
UFO> sum(5)
sum(1) = 1
calculated sum(2) = 3
calculated sum(3) = 6
calculated sum(4) = 10
calculated sum(5) = 15
15 :: Integer
%%%

A second call shows that the recursive calls are not done:

%%%
UFO> sum(5)
15 :: Integer
%%%

Have a look at the cache:

%%%
UFO> cache
#{2=3, 3=6, 4=10, 5=15} :: HashTable
%%%

That shows a table of mappings of the form `n=sum(n)`.

Calling `sum` with a larger number causes it to calculate only the values starting from the first number not found in the cache:

%%%
UFO> sum(10)
calculated sum(6) = 21
calculated sum(7) = 28
calculated sum(8) = 36
calculated sum(9) = 45
calculated sum(10) = 55
55 :: Integer
%%%

Let's push it all the way up to 100:

%%%
UFO> sum(100)
...
calculated sum(97) = 4753
calculated sum(98) = 4851
calculated sum(99) = 4950
calculated sum(100) = 5050
5050 :: Integer
%%%

Then try 101:

%%%
UFO> sum(101)
calculated sum(101) = 5151
5151 :: Integer
%%%

Nice! It had to do only one recursive call.

But now calling `sum(n)` on any number from 1 to 101 requires only a cache lookup!

If we had a larger program that made many calls to the `sum` function all within a certain upper bound of //n//, then the longer the program runs the more more calls to `sum` would be resolved with just a cache lookup. Initially the `sum` function runs in [[linear time|Writing programs: Time complexity: Linear]], but the longer it runs the closer it gets to [[constant time|Writing programs: Time complexity: Constant]].

Thus, we say that the [[amortized time complexity|https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Amortized_analysis]] of this version of the `sum` function is [[O(1)|Writing programs: Time complexity: Constant]]. This is a common characteristic of memoized functions.

!Automatic memoization

The cached version of the `sum` function is messy compared to the non-cached version:

''Cached version''

%%%
let cache = #{}
fun sum(1) = 1
 |     (n) = let res = cache.get(n) in
               if res is nil then
                 res := n + sum(n - 1)
                 cache[n] := res
               end
               res
             end
end
%%%

''Non-cached version''

%%%
fun sum(1) = 1
 |     (n) = n + sum(n - 1)
end
%%%

UFO includes a feature that lets you memoize a function automatically. This is done when the function is defined, and the only difference is the use of the reserved word `fun#` instead of `fun` (the `#` character reminds you that a hash table is being used for the memo cache).

%%%
fun# sum(1) = 1
 |      (n) = n + sum(n - 1)
end
%%%

When you call that function all you see is the final value. There's no indication of when the body is being evaluated or when the memo cache returned a value.

Here I've added some instrumentation to the function so that we can see what's happening:

%%%
fun# sum(1) = 1
 |      (n) = let res = n + sum(n - 1) in
                io:displn("calculated sum(", n, ") = ", res)
                res
              end
end
%%%

Call it:

%%%
UFO> sum(10)
calculated sum(2) = 3
calculated sum(3) = 6
calculated sum(4) = 10
calculated sum(5) = 15
calculated sum(6) = 21
calculated sum(7) = 28
calculated sum(8) = 36
calculated sum(9) = 45
calculated sum(10) = 55
55 :: Integer
%%%

Call it again:

%%%
UFO> sum(10)
55 :: Integer
%%%

Memoizing a function is a tradeoff of time vs. space: a memoized function takes less time to run, but its memo cache uses more space.

Here's the elapsed time for first run of the memoized `sum` function

%%%
UFO> time:elapsed('sum(100)')
{0, 9218262} :: Array
%%%

That's 0 seconds and 9218262 nanoseconds, or about 0.0092 seconds. Subsequent calls to `sum` are much faster:

%%%
UFO> time:elapsed('sum(100)')
{0, 46208} :: Array
UFO> time:elapsed('sum(99)')
{0, 42879} :: Array
%%%

That's about 0.000045 seconds.






Each //primitive// (or //built-in//) function is contained in a //namespace//.

Each namespace contains a collection of closely related functions. For example, each [[collection data type|Data type: Collection]] has a namespace with a group of primitives that can be called on it.

|!Data type |!Namespace |
|[[Array|Data type: Array]] |[[array|Namespace: array]] |
|[[Binding|Data type: Binding]] |[[binding|Namespace: binding]] |
|[[HashTable|Data type: HashTable]] |[[hash|Namespace: hash]] |
|[[List|Data type: List]] |[[list|Namespace: list]] |
|[[Queue|Data type: Queue]] |[[queue|Namespace: queue]] |
|[[Seq|Data type: Seq]] |[[seq|Namespace: seq]] |
|[[Set|Data type: Set]] |[[set|Namespace: set]] |
|[[Stack|Data type: Stack]] |[[stack|Namespace: stack]] |
|[[Term|Data type: Term]] |[[term|Namespace: term]] |

Each namespace is actually a UFO [[hash table|Data type: HashTable]]. If you type the name of a namespace in the command shell, UFO will show you the hash table:

%%%
UFO> io
#{fmt=fmt(fmtStr :: String, bindings), show=show(...), displn=displn(...), showString=showString(...), readLine=readLine(...), disp=disp(...), nl=nl(), showln=showln(...), dispString=dispString(...)} :: HashTable
%%%

That looks kind of messy. You can call the `hash:keys` function on that hash table to see just the keys, which are just the names of the primitive functions in that namespace:

%%%
UFO> hash:keys(io)
${fmt, show, displn, showString, readLine, disp, nl, showln, dispString} :: Set
%%%

A primitive is referred to by using its fully-qualified name, which is its namespace name and its function name separated by a colon. For example, the `displn` (//display line//) primitive is contained in the `io` namespace, so you refer to the function like this:

%%%
UFO> io:displn
displn(...) :: Primitive
%%%

The ellipsis `...` indicates that it accepts any number of arguments of any type.

To call a function, use its fully-qualified name and supply arguments in parentheses:

%%%
UFO> io:displn("Hello, World!")
Hello, World!
%%%

!See also
* [[Reference: Namespace]]






This explains the differences between the three operators `=`, `==`, and `:=`.

!The '=' operator
This constructs a `Binding`.

%%%
UFO> A=10
A=10 :: Binding
%%%

See [[Data type: Binding]].

!The '==' operator
This is the //equality// comparison operator. It checks if two values are equal and returns either `true` or `false`.

See [[Operator: Equal to]].

!The ':=' operator
This is the //assignment// operator. This assigns (or re-assigns) a value to an identifier or collection.

See [[Operator: Assignment]].






Every operator can also be used as if it were a standard identifier.

%%%
UFO> 1 + 2
3 :: Integer
%%%

%%%
UFO> +
+(lhs :: Numeric, rhs :: Numeric) :: Primitive
%%%

%%%
UFO> +(1, 2)
3 :: Integer
%%%






Pattern matching is used in several different places in UFO to bind values to identifiers.

The `let` expression is usually used to bind single identifiers, but pattern matching can be used to bind multiple identifiers at once:

%%%
UFO> let [x, y] = [100, 200]
UFO> x
100 :: Integer
UFO> y
200 :: Integer
%%%

This works with most collection data types. Parentheses may be needed to avoid ambiguity, like with the bindings `x=y` and `A=B`:

%%%
UFO> let (x=y) = (A=B)
UFO> x
A :: Symbol
UFO> y
B :: Symbol
%%%

!Matching function parameters

Consider this function:

%%%
UFO> let f = fun (0) = Zero | (1) = One | (2) = Two end
%%%

It has three rules:

%%%
(0) = Zero
(1) = One
(2) = Two
%%%

When the argument `0` is supplied the function returns the symbol `Zero`, `1` returns `One`, and `2` returns `Two`.

Let's test it:

%%%
UFO> f(0)
Zero :: Symbol
UFO> f(1)
One :: Symbol
UFO> f(2)
Two :: Symbol
%%%

The inverse of function ''f'' can easily be written:

%%%
UFO> let g = fun (Zero) = 0 | (One) = 1 | (Two) = 2 end
%%%

Test it:

%%%
UFO> g(Zero)
0 :: Integer
UFO> g(One)
1 :: Integer
UFO> g(Two)
2 :: Integer
%%%

Pattern matching is an important aspect of writing [[recursive functions|Writing programs: Recursion and tail recursion]].

!Matching duplicate parameters

Consider this function with two rules:

%%%
fun f(x, x) = Same{x}
 |   (x, y) = Different{x, y}
end
%%%

The first rule matches only if the first parameter and the second parameter are the same. The second rule matches any two parameters, and only if the first rule doesn't match.

When a function is called, if a parameter is bound to an argument value then subsequent uses of that parameter in the same rule must match the same argument value.

%%%
UFO> f(1,1)
Same{1} :: Term
%%%
%%%
UFO> f(1,2)
Different{1, 2} :: Term
%%%

Observe what happens if the two rules are swapped:

%%%
fun f(x, y) = Different{x, y}
 |   (x, x) = Same{x}
end
%%%

In that function the first rule always matches:

%%%
UFO> f(1, 1)
Different{1, 1} :: Term
UFO> f(1, 2)
Different{1, 2} :: Term
%%%

!Matching data structures

Data structures can also be used as parameter patterns:

%%%
fun f({x}) = Array{x}
 |   ([x]) = List{x}
 |   (x=y) = Binding{x, y}
end
%%%

%%%
UFO> f({1})
Array{1} :: Term
%%%
%%%
UFO> f([1])
List{1} :: Term
%%%
%%%
UFO> f(A=1)
Binding{A, 1} :: Term
%%%






!Recursion
Recursion is a situation where a function makes a call to itself, or where a function calls another function that in turn calls the first function. Recursion takes a while to get used to if you're not experienced with it, but it can be an extremely powerful means of programming.

You can also have a look at the [[tutorial page on recursion|Tutorial 21. Recursion]].

!A list example
Lists and recursion go together like [[milk and cookies|https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Milk_and_Cookies]].

Here's a function that can be used to count the number of elements in a list:

%%%
UFO> fun len([]) = 0 | ([_|rest]) = 1 + len(rest) end
%%%

(Note that it's not necessary to use this function to count a list since the [[list:count|Primitive: list:count]] primitive exists, but I'll continue with this example because it's a good one to learn from.)

The function might be easier to understand if it's formatted on multiple lines:

%%%
fun len([]) = 0
     | ([_|rest]) = 1 + len(rest) end
%%%

There are two rules:

* If `len` is called with the empty list `[]`, then it returns 0.
* if `len` is called with a non-empty list, it maches the pattern `[_|rest]`. The first element of the list matches `_` [[and is ignored|Writing programs: Anonymous identifier]], and the rest of the list matches `rest`. The return value of that rule is 1 + `len` of that now-shorter list.

!Tail call elimination and tail recursion
The UFO evaluator supports proper //tail call elimination//. This is a mechanism in the evaluator whereby the final function call (or method call) in any sequence does not cause a stack frame to accumulate.

The [[Wikipedia article on tail call elimination|https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tail_call]] describes it better than I could. Please see that article for more information.

It's hard to see tail call elimination in action in the general sense, but when the tail call is a recursive call then it's called //tail recursion//, and it's very powerful.

First, consider the recursive `len` function from above:

%%%
fun len([]) = 0
     | ([_|rest]) = 1 + len(rest) end
%%%

It looks as though the final function call of the second rule is `len(rest)` and that this should be a tail call, right? No! The final function call of that rule is actually the infix operator `1 + len(rest)`, which is the same as a function call, only it's in a slightly different form. That operator call doesn't finish until after the call to `len(rest)` finishes. The operator `1 +` can't finish until it knows what the value of `len(rest)` is. That call to `len(rest)` might cause `1 + len(rest)` to be called again, and so on. It eventually terminates with a call to `len([])`, at which time the previous calls to `len(rest)` and `1 + len(rest)` are able to complete. Each of these nested calls causes a call frame to accumulate on the call stack, and when the call finishes the call frame is popped off the stack.

The danger with this kind of function is that with too many recursive function calls, the call stack could become so deep that the evaluator runs out of memory. This is called a //stack overflow//.

Here's a different function:

%%%
fun countDown(0) = Done
     | (n) = countDown(n - 1)
end
%%%

The final function call (the //only// function call) of the second rule is `countDown(n - 1)`. This function call needs to call the operator `n - 1`, but that completes before the call to `countDown` is made. Thus, each call to `countDown(n - 1)` has nothing waiting for its value, so each call to `countDown` does not cause an additional stack frame to accumulate.

When the //tail call// (final function call) of a function is a recursive function call, the function is said to be //tail recursive//.

!Converting from left recursion to tail recursion
The `len` example above is not tail recursive. Parser writers call that kind of recursion //left recursion//, so that's what I'll call it here.

It's possible to convert any left recursive function into a tail recursive one, but it usually requires an additional function parameter that, in a way, acts like the call stack.

Here's a tail recursive version of the `len` function from above:

%%%
fun len(lst) = len(lst, 0)
     | ([], n) = n
     | ([_|rest], n) = len(rest, n + 1)
end
%%%

# The first rule takes any value in the `lst` variable and calls one of the other two rules, depending on which one it matches, with the addition of the argument 0: this is an //accumulator// value that indicates how many elements in the list have been counted so far.
# The second rule is the base case that terminates the recursion: if the list is empty, return the number of elements that have been counted.
# The third rule just calls `len` with the rest of the list and the value of `n + 1`, indicating that we've counted one additional value.

!See also
* [[Example: quicksort]]






!About time complexity
It's important to understand the //time complexity// of the functions you write in order to avoid unexpected slow-downs as your program becomes more complex, or as the data sets your program uses become larger.

Note that time complexity is never presented in actual [[wall clock time|https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elapsed_real_time]]. Instead it lets you answer the question

> //If I increase the size of this function's input by some amount, how much longer will the function take to run?//

In other words, if you double the size of a function's input, will it still run in the same amount of time? Will it take twice as long to run? Or four times as long? This is an important consideration when you're attempting to write an efficient program (or at least to avoid writing an inefficient program).

I won't go into all the details here (see the [[Wikipedia article on time complexity|https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Time_complexity]]) but I will present an example.

Consider this function that creates a square matrix of ''n'' rows and ''n'' columns:

%%%
fun sq(n) =
  let mat = array:new(n);
  loop i=n do
    mat[i] := array:new(n, 0)
  end;
  mat
end
%%%

There's a single loop in that function and it looks as though the time taken by that function is proportional to ''n''. But if you have a look at the [[array:new|Primitive: array:new]] primitive, you can see that it takes time proportional to the number of elements in the array. Thus, [[array:new|Primitive: array:new]] is a linear-time operation proportional to ''n'', and the function is doing that operation inside the loop a number of times equal to ''n'': that means that the `sq` operation takes time proportional to ''n'' x ''n'', or ''n''^^2^^. The `sq` function runs in [[quadratic time|Writing programs: Time complexity: Quadratic]].

For a 10 x 10 matrix, that's 100 operations. But for a 100 x 100 matrix, that's 10,000 operations.

!Big-O notation
Computer scientists often use the //big-O// notation to indicate the time complexity of a function. It indicates the average (arithmetic mean) amount of time a function is expected to take relative to the size of the function's input.

; O(//1//)
: [[Constant time|Writing programs: Time complexity: Constant]]: The function runs in the same amount of time regardless of the size of the input.

; O(//n//)
: [[Linear time|Writing programs: Time complexity: Linear]]: The function takes an amount of time that's directly proportional to the size of the input.

; O(//n log n//)
: [[Quasilinear|Writing programs: Time complexity: Quasilinear]]: The function takes an amount of time that's proportional to the size of the input times the log of the size of the input: ×

; O(//n^^2^^//)
: [[Quadratic time|Writing programs: Time complexity: Quadratic]]: The function takes an amount of time that's proportional to the square of the size of the input.

There are quite a few other time complexities, but these are the ones most commonly seen. Computer scientists generally consider an //efficient// program anything that avoids the worse of the time complexities. Constant time is great. Linear time is usually ok. Quadratic time is not so good.

!Size of the input
The "size" of a function's input often refers to the size of an array or list or some other data structure. It can also refer to the value of a number that controls the size of some other value, or the number of iterations that the function ends up making. In the `sq(n)` function above, the //size of the input// is the same as //the value of ''n''//.

!//Efficient// and //fast// aren't the same thing
Be aware that even a constant-time function can still be slow by wall clock standards:

%%%
fun f(x) = time:sleep(100_000) end
%%%

That function takes 100 seconds to complete, but it does exhibit ''O(//1//)'' behavior: no matter what the input to that function is, it always takes 100 seconds to complete.

Conversely, a function that exibits ''O(//n^^2^^//)'' behavior but is written in assembly language and highly optimized could possibly run //extremely fast// even with large inputs. But the danger with a function like that is that there could potentially be an input large enough that the time delay becomes noticeable, or even unacceptable.

!Time complexity of primitives
Many of the primitive functions described in this document have the time complexity shown for the primitive. This time complexity applies only in the case where the collection contains atomic values and the element being searched in the collection is an atomic value, whereby comparison of two atoms takes [[O(1)|Writing programs: Time complexity: Constant]] time.






!O(//1//)

This is an operation whose time remains constant regardless of the size of the input.

!See also
* https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Time_complexity#Constant_time







!O(//n//)

This is an operation that takes an amount of time proportional to the size of the input.

!See also
* https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Time_complexity#Linear_time







!O(//n^^2^^//)

This is an operation that takes an amount of time proportional to the //square// of the size of the input.

!See also
* https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Time_complexity#Sub-quadratic_time







!O(//n log n//)

This is an operation that takes an amount of time proportional to ''//n// × log //n//'', which is greater than ''O(//n//)'' but less than ''O(//n//^^2^^)''.

!See also
* https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Time_complexity#Quasilinear_time







The conversion of a value to a different data type can be done with either the [[type:convert|Primitive: type:convert]] primitive or the [[:>|Operator: Type convert]] operator.

A collection of any type can be converted to its own type, and doing so makes a shallow copy of that collection.

Furthermore, the following conversions are supported:
<<tabs "[[Type conversion: Array]] [[Type conversion: Binding]] [[Type conversion: Boolean]] [[Type conversion: HashTable]] [[Type conversion: Integer]] [[Type conversion: List]] [[Type conversion: Queue]] [[Type conversion: Real]] [[Type conversion: Seq]] [[Type conversion: Set]] [[Type conversion: String]] [[Type conversion: StringBuffer]] [[Type conversion: Stack]] [[Type conversion: Symbol]] [[Type conversion: Term]]" "" "" "tc-vertical">>






Every value in UFO has a type associated with it.

; Getting a value's type
: `type:name(x)`
: Returns a value's type as a [[symbol|Data type: Symbol]].

; Converting to a new type
: `x :> type`
: `type:convert(x, type)`
: Converts `x` to the type specified by `type`, which should be (or evaluate to) a [[symbol|Data type: Symbol]].
: See: [[Primitive: type:convert]], [[Operator: Type convert]]

; Type check predicate
: `x :? type`
: `type:hasType(type)`
: Checks that `x` has the type specified by `type`, which should be (or evaluate to) a [[symbol|Data type: Symbol]].
: Returns `true` on success, or `false` on failure.
: See: [[Primitive: type:hasType]], [[Operator: Type predicate]]

; Type check assertion
: `x :: type`
: `type:check(x, type)`
: Checks that `x` has the type specified by `type`, which should be (or evaluate to) a [[symbol|Data type: Symbol]].
: Returns `x` on success, or throws a `WrongType` exception on failure.
: See: [[Primitive: type:check]], [[Operator: Type check]]

!See also
* [[Writing programs: Type conversion]]






!Value
A value is something that evaluates to a thing of the same type. All the [[atom and collection data types|Reference: Data type]] are values.

!Expression
An expression is something that evaluates to a thing of a different type. Any program statement that's not an atom or collection, [[like an `if` statement, `loop` statement, or function application|Reference: Expression]].
